<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chrysler Introduces New Plastic Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Chrysler Motor Co., the third
largest car maker of the U.S., is close to turn out a plastic car
body that needs no paint and could halve the price of a car.
</P>
<P>
Using common beverage bottle plastic called PET -- for
polyethylene terephthalate -- the automaker has been able to
fabricate body parts big enough that a car body could consist of
just six pieces instead of 80 or so, according to a report of the
USA Today Monday.
</P>
<P>
Color is molded throughout the plastic. That eliminates the
need for a car factory's costly, slow-paced painting process.
</P>
<P>
The paint shop is the largest single expense of building a
factory, and a bottleneck that slows production, it is said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that eliminating painting, expensive metal
stamping and forming, and gluing together six body pieces instead
of welding dozens, could cut manufacturing costs enough that a PET
car could be half the price of a conventional vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Building a PET factory could cost as little as one-third the 1
billion U.S. dollar cost of building a conventional car factory.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler says that the car would be as safe in a crash as other
cars it sells, and it is developing special techniques that would
let body shops repair minor damage cheaply and easily.
</P>
<P>
Plastic-bodied cars would use conventional metal chassis, but
Chrysler's plastic car bodies does not require a steel skeleton as
other factories often use, thus making the car bodies lighter and
less expensive.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the company is planning a PET car in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
