<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits High of 132.9 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a high of
132.9 yen in Tokyo late Monday, reaching the 132 yen level for the
first time since May 1992.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 132.83-86 yen at 5 p.m.local
time, up from 132.07-10 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 132.30-40
yen late Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
The dollar mostly held steady in the 132 yen level, backed by
lower Tokyo stock prices and the weak Southeast Asian currencies,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section at the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished the half-day session
below the psychologically important 15,000 point line, falling
more than 300 points to 14,956.84.
</P>
<P>
The persistent weakness of Southeast Asian currencies also
helped the dollar-buying mood against the yen, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
One dealer at a Japanese bank said that the Japanese yen would
probably continue to face selling pressure unless the government
implements further strong measures to boost the domestic economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
