<HEADLINE> Austria, Finland Likely to Host Ulster Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Austrian and Finnish
governments have offered to host the Northern Ireland peace talks
on neutral ground, according to Irish government sources.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern was quoted
by Reuters as saying today: "There is nothing in writing, but
Austria and Finland have offered to host the talks."
</P>
<P>
"As far as I understand the invitations are open-ended," the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland peace process has run into fresh
difficulties as violence broke out in late December when a
hardline loyalist Billy Wright was killed in a high-security
Belfast prison.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Loyalist groups have staged several attacks
upon Catholic districts of Belfast, killing two people.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Ahern, as a co-sponsor of the peace talks,
said that it was time to take big steps in pushing forward the
peace talks, according to a report in the Irish Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"I do believe, despite all the atrocities and all the terrible
deeds over the last week, there is a real opportunity now to make
significant progress in the early months of 1998," Ahern said.
</P>
</TEXT>
