<HEADLINE> U.S.: Levy's Quit will not Affect Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
said the resignation of Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
should not affect the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Middle East peace process has always continued in its
sometimes measured way despite internal political developments
affecting the government of Israel," White House spokesman Mike
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Levy announced his decision of resignation on Sunday after a
dispute with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over social
policy and the peace process. His move has reduced Netanyahu's
Likud-led ruling coalition to a one-vote majority in the
Knesset, the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said that "individuals and the role individual
cabinet members play in the process change from time to time but
the process continues."
</P>
<P>
The White House on Sunday announced that President Bill
Clinton will meet Netanyahu in Washington on Jan. 20 and then
hold talks two days later with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
in an attempt to revitalize the Middle East peace process that
all but died last year because of Israel's decision to build
Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
