<HEADLINE> Kazakh President Lists 1997 Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev said here Monday the economic and political reforms in
his country achieved positive results in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As shown by statistics, Nazarbayev told a ceremony for the
opening of a university, Kazakhstan's gross domestic product (GDP)
grew 2.5 percent in 1997 to reach per capita 1,500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth is recognized by the World Bank as among the
highest in the Commonwealth of Independent States, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the annual inflation in the country stood at 12
percent, significantly lower than the government's projection of
17.5 percent, and savings by Kazakh residents rose 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
And of the total 6.2 billion dollars direct foreign investment
in Kazakhstan over the past five years, 1.7 billion dollars came
into the country in 1997, the president said.
</P>
<P>
As a market economy has taken shape, he said, it would serve as
a solid foundation for the country's further economic growth and
the implementation of its long-term development strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
