<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Fuel Facilities Project Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on the
Sapugaskanda fuel facilities, to be carried out by a Chinese
company, was officially inaugurated in the northern suburb of the
capital city Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Irrigation and Power Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte and
Chinese Chemical Industry Minister Gu Xiulian, who arrived here
last Friday at the invitation of President Chandrika Kumaratunga
and Ratwatte, attended the inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Under the construction project, the China Huanqiu Chemical
Engineering Corporation (HQCEC) is to build a mini-terminal and
some oil tanks for the Ceylon Petroleum Corporation (CPC).
</P>
<P>
The CPC will use a soft loan of 24 million U.S. dollars
provided by the Asian Development Bank to fund the project, the
costs of which have been estimated at around 21 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Besides helping construct the facilities, the HQCEC will also
rehabilitate other tanks which were damaged by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam in nearby CPC oil facilities on October 20,
1995.
</P>
<P>
Ratwatte said at the ceremony that China and Sri Lanka have a
long history of cooperation in economic and cultural fields and he
hoped such cooperation could continue.
</P>
<P>
Gu Xiulian said the start of the construction work marked a
good beginning of the cooperation between the Chinese chemical
industry and the Sri Lankan energy industry.
</P>
<P>
HQCEC President He Lishan, whose company beat all the other 86
international bidders to become the sole contractor of the
project, assured the Sri Lankan side that his company will finish
the project ahead of schedule with high quality and low costs.
</P>
<P>
The construction will take about 22 months to finish.  
</P>
</TEXT>
