<HEADLINE> France Calls for Protection of Algerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- France Monday urged the Algerian
government to protect "the legitimate right" of the Algerian
people while condemning the newest "terrorist crimes" committed
against the civilians of the country.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time France has openly addressed the Algerian
government, in whose regime massacres of civilians are reported
almost every day.
</P>
<P>
Four hundred Algerians were reportedly killed from Tuesday
night to Wednesday morning, the first day of the Muslim fasting
month of Ramadan, in Relizane, of western Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The French address came one day after Germany asked the
European Union (EU) to call for an emergency meeting on Algeria
and suggested that the EU send a delegation to Algeria to discuss
with the Algerian government measures the EU can take to help
fight Islamic militants there.
</P>
<P>
"The duty of all governments is to allow its citizens to live
in peace and in security," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
The newest violence perpetuated by Islamic militants, Doutriaux
said, "cannot find any justification, and above all religious."
</P>
<P>
"The French authorities are deeply upset and angered by the
acts of savageness and barbarity which have once again struck the
Algerian people at the moment when they are celebrating the
Ramadan," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Doutriaux described the German proposal "a good idea" and
expressed support to "all initiatives susceptible of manifesting
the solidarity of the international community with the Algerian
people."
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that France "attaches the greatest
importance" to providing aid to the families of the victims of
massacres and to "what allows promote a peaceful and democratic
solution to the crisis in Algeria." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
