<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Economy may experience Sharp Downturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The prospect of a sharp downturn
in the British economy during 1998 is underscored by leading
forecasters.
</P>
<P>
This would be a result of high interest rates, an over-valued
sterling and the British government's tight fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts were released on Monday by the National Institute
of Economic and Social Research (NIESR), Oxford Economic
Forecasting (OEF) and Cambridge Econometrics.
</P>
<P>
Their forecasts suggest that the economy could face another
boom-bust ride. Annual growth is projected to fall from around 3.5
per cent in 1997 to close to 2 per cent in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
If the projections prove correct, Britain will have the slowest
growth rate of all 15 EU members in 1998 after enjoying some of
the best growth conditions in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Cambridge Econometrics forecasts growth to fall to 2.5 per cent
this year, adding that further steep reductions will occur in
1999.
</P>
<P>
OEF predicts that base rates, currently at 7.25 per cent, will
rise again before falling back to about 6.75 per cent by the end
of 1998 and 6.25 per cent by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
The Oxford forecaster says: "The turmoil in Asia is likely to
have a bigger impact on the UK than generally acknowledged.
Including Japan, Asia accounts for 11.5 per cent of UK exports and
3.5 per cent of gross domestic product."
</P>
<P>
It warns that if the continuing turmoil in Asia triggers a
worldwide collapse in share prices, Britain's growth prospect
could fall to just 1.5 per cent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The strength of the pound is also highlighted by Cambridge
Econometrics which is relatively optimistic about UK's economy in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The forecasters expect Britain's current account to swing from
2.5 billion pounds (4 billion U.S. dollars) surplus in 1997 to a
deficit of almost 6 billion pounds (9.6 billion U.S. dollars) this
year and 7 billion pounds (11.2 billion U.S. dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
They also warn the danger that the Bank of England may prove
reluctant to bring interest rates down again quickly enough during
the course of this year as the slowdown becomes evident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
