<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Airspace at Risk, Say Controllers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's dismissed air traffic
controllers today said that the government is putting the country's
airspace at risk by engaging Zambian controllers who have been
undergoing training in Zimbabwe since December 23.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Air Traffic Controllers Association of Zimbabwe
(ATCAZ) said in a statement that the situation in civil aviation is far
from normal despite contrary claims by the government.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Zambians' qualifications are far below
those required for local air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
"The Zambian airspace itself is internationally blacklisted
because of inadequate and non-standard training of controllers, the
high number of aircraft incidents and poor state of equipment," the
ATCAZ said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government dismissed 67 air traffic controllers in
December last year after they started a strike to protest poor
working conditions and salaries.
</P>
<P>
The association said the government had already
authorized that the Zambian controllers be allowed to start operating
after only two weeks training.
</P>
<P>
"Local and more experienced controllers are taking an average of
18 months to reach the required standards of proficiency," the ATCAZ
said.
</P>
<P>
The association denied claims by the government authorities that
they had sabotaged the civil aviation equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
