<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Less Foreign Capital Flows Into Vietnam in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investments in Vietnam
were down from 9.20 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 to 5.55 billion
in 1997, the Ministry of Planning and Investment (MPI) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Vietnam granted licences to 336 direct foreign
investment projects worth over 4.45 billion dollars, and permitted
143 existing projects to bring in 1.1 billion more, the MPI said.
</P>
<P>
Of the contracted capital inflow, 2.95 billion dollars was
disbursed in the year, a 34 percent annual increase, or the
highest since the foreign investment law was enacted 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Investments in Vietnam's manufacturing, construction and
agricultural sectors took the biggest shares, it said.
</P>
<P>
Japan topped other foreign investors in 1997 with 875 million
dollars, followed by South Korea and France.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam currently hosts a total of 2,320 overseas investment
projects with a registered capital of over 35.04 billion dollars,
among which nearly 11.88 billion dollars has been disbursed.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government will formulate some favorable
policies to attract more foreign investments in manufacturing
operations and in the country's remote areas, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
