<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Declines in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The nation-wide construction
spending fell 0.9 percent in November, the worst decline in 11
months last year, the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The decline, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 609
billion U.S. dollars, was recorded following four consecutive
increases, the report said.
</P>
<P>
October's increase, previously estimated at a slight 0.1
percent, was revised to a sharp 1.4 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The spending decrease in November was led by a 3.8 percent
decline in non-residential commercial construction to a rate of
158.7 billion dollars. Meanwhile, spending on hotels, offices,
hospitals and shopping centers all declined. It was the sector's
third drop in four months.
</P>
<P>
Government construction fell 0.5 percent to a rate of 140.6
billion dollars. However, spending on highways and streets shot up
10.7 percent to an all-time high. But public housing and
redevelopment, schools, public hospitals and water and sewer
systems all declined.
</P>
<P>
Housing construction increased 0.9 percent to a rate of 268.6
billion dollars. An increase in single-family construction to a
record high and a rise in remodeling spending offset a drop in
apartment construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
