<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Trade Deficit Up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' trade deficit in the
first eight months of 1997 amounted to 826.6 million Cyprus pounds
(about 1.65 billion U.S. dollars), a 4.2 percent increase over the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued today by the Cypriot Department of
Statistics and Research, total imports from January to August in
1997 valued at 1.25 billion Cyprus pounds (2.5 billion dollars)
compared with 1.2 billion pounds (around 2.45 billion dollars) in
the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's total exports decreased to 424.6 million pounds
(849.2 million dollars) in comparison with 432.7 million pounds
(865.4 million dollars) in the first eight months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the European Union (EU) countries'
export to Cyprus valued at 583.1 million pounds (1.17 billion
dollars) during the period, accounting for 46.6 percent of the
total imports of this island nation.
</P>
<P>
For Cyprus' export, the EU countries absorbed 50.4 percent of
the total in the first eight months of 1997, followed by the Arab
countries with 27.3 percent, while in the 1996 January-August
period, the shares of the EU countries and the Arab countries were
59.8 percent and 17.9 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
