<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Send Observer to Turkey-Israel-US Wargame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Despite wide criticism from other
Arab countries, Jordan decided today to send one observer for the
upcoming navy exercises in the Mediterranean which involve troops
from Turkey, Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh today confirmed to
reporters that Jordan would not participate in the wargame
scheduled for January 7, but send there one observer instead.
</P>
<P>
Top navy officer Hussein Hasawneh will leave Amman later today
on such a mission, Tarawneh said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Arab countries' criticism against Jordan's
involvement in the exercises, Tarawneh said that Jordan made the
decision in order to defend its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The wargame did not have a combating role and Jordan treated it
as exercises for research and rescue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said earlier that the exercises were open to all the
Arab countries, but only Jordan has responded positively to its
invitation up to now.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, which are widely thought to target Syria and
Iraq, have been drawing harsh criticism from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and Iraq are spearheading an Arab campaign
against the growing military cooperation between Turkey and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Ambassador to Jordan Ahmet Suha Omar earlier
told semi-official Jordan Times that the wargame was "merely
rescue and search exercises ... for humanitarian reasons only."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel started their military cooperation in 1996
when the two countries signed two military cooperation
agreements. The two sides are discussing several defense-related
projects.
</P>
<P>
After Jordan signed a peace agreement with Israel in 1994, the
two countries have conducted one joint military drill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
