<HEADLINE> Zambian President Calls for Independence From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
today called on the Zambians to be self-reliant to defend his
country's sovereignty, Zambia News Agency Zana reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the supporters of the ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) in the State House, Chiluba said that
the Zambians must be self-reliant instead of depending on donors
for all the resources.
</P>
<P>
"We will not enjoy our sovereignty if we depend on donors even for
salaries," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He strongly criticized some African and Western donors since they
interfered wantonly in Zambia's internal affairs and wanted to
dictated terms to the MMD government.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba's remarks came after foreign leaders tried to push his
government to release the detained former president and opposition
leader Kenneth Kaunda who is allegedly to be involved in the country
abortive military coup last October.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, Chiluba also warned foreign media that they
should portray the "positive" development taking success in the country
instead of always depicting the bad side.
</P>
<P>
He noted that despite the bottle necks in the implementation of
development programs, the government has scored successes in a
number of programs like the privatization of the mines and road
construction and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The former trade union leader, who came to power in 1991 and was
re-elected in 1996, also appealed to investors to come and invest into
the country where natural resources for agriculture and other
activities are in abundance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
