<HEADLINE> Egypt to Try Suspected Israeli Spy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Higher State Security Court of
Egypt today ordered an Egyptian accused of spying for Israel to be
remanded in custody for 45 extra days before putting him on trial,
the Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Samir Othman, 47, was arrested one and a half year ago in Taba,
about 360 kilometers southeast of Cairo, where he worked, on
charges of transferring military information to the Israeli
intelligence agency Mossad.
</P>
<P>
Now that this is the last renewal of the custody period, the
Higher State Security Prosecution is expected to issue an
indictment sheet within days in preparation for his trial.
</P>
<P>
Othman's papers had been referred to the Military Prosecution,
but were sent back to the State Security Prosecution. MENA gave
the reason as that the military information stolen by the
defendant is old and therefore he should stand trial before a
civil court.
</P>
<P>
The trial came five months after the same court sentenced Azam
Azam, an Israeli textile engineer accused of spying for Israel, to
15 years in prison last August.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that Azam's Egyptian colleague, Emad Abdel
Hamid, be imprisoned for life in the same case.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old Azam and 34-year-old Hamid, arrested in
November, 1996, had pleaded innocence to charges of spying for the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have a peace treaty with
Israel but ties have never been warm. The spy cases, however,
added to the tensions caused by the Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
