<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Rate Falls to Single Digit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said it has successfully
curbed price increases and brought the inflation rate to 8.5
percent by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The single digit inflation rate compared to 72.8 percent in
december 1995 and 29 percent in 1996, said Head of State General
Sani Abacha, who presented the government 1998 budget last night.
</P>
<P>
In his review of the 1997 budget, Abacha said the positive
developments in the country's economy were also reflected in the
largely stable exchange rate of national currency, reduced
foreign debt stock and increased foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Nigeria recorded a foreign debt stock of
27 billion U.S. dollars, a drop of one billion from one year
earlier, while foreign exchange reserves surged 88.4 percent
year-on-year to 7.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the government failed to meet the set goal for
economic growth in 1997, although "marked improvement" had been
made.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide broadcast, Abacha said the estimated growth
rate of Gross Domestic Product was 3.77 percent, lower than the
target of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector also recorded a decline from 1.02
percent in 1996 to 0.72 percent in 1997, despite a slight
improvement in capacity utilization, from 32.5 percent to 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
Abacha did not explain why the government failed to achieve
the growth target, but analysts attributed the failure partly to
the late disbursement of capital votes to the ministries and the
continued serious feul scarcity in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1998 budget, abacha said the growth target this
year is set at 5.5 percent and the average annual growth rate
between 1998 and 2000 will be 6.19 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
