<HEADLINE> UK to Hold Annual Survey on NHS Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
decided to hold annual nationwide surveys starting this year on
the quality of the National Health Service (NHS) treatment as part
of an initiative to raise standards, local press reports said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time such audit of the NHS will
be conducted in history.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a random sample of up to 100,000
patients will be questioned on the quality of food, the
use of painkillers after operations, the standard of
nursing care and how well they were treated by their
family doctors and consultants.
</P>
<P>
Survey results will be published every year on a health
authority basis, to show the best and worst services
offered by health authorities.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed to force an improvement in standards
and also reflects the growing move by the public and
private sector to treat patients as customers and clients
using a service, rather than people who should be grateful
for doctors sparing the time to see them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
