<HEADLINE> Jordan's FM: Levy's Resignation to Affect Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The resignation of Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy will adversely affect the Middle East peace
process, Jordanian Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh told
reporters today.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation Sunday will create a crisis in the Israeli
government and give Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu new excuses
for not implementing the agreements already signed with the
Palestinians, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Such a resignation may delay the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process for six months or even longer, Tarawneh said.
</P>
<P>
When he announced his resignation Sunday, Levy bitterly
denounced the 19-month-old Netanyahu government for both
abandoning the peace process with the Arabs and ignoring the
mounting problems of Israel's poor and unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks suffered setbacks since
Israel began construction of Jewish settlements in controversial
Arab East Jerusalem in March, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on the Lebanese and Syrian tracks were also
stalemated due to Netanyahu government's hardline policy.
</P>
