<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Recommends to Extend Mandate of UNMOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan today recommended to extend the mandate
of the United Nations Mission of Observers in Prevlaka (UNMOP) for
a further period of six months until July 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, Annan said in
accordance with resolution 1119, UNMOP continues to monitor the
demilitarization of the Prevlaka Peninsula and of the
neighboring areas in Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the situation in the UNMOP area of
responsibility has remained stable, occasional violations of the
demilitarization regime were fewer in number and of lesser
significance than similar violations reported in the past.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said Croatia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia have continued to reiterate their firm commitment
to a negotiated resolution of the disputed issue of Prevlaka in
accordance with their agreement on Normalization of Relations.
</P>
<P>
Annan said but substantive negotiations have not started and
Croatian and Yugoslav officials have held out no prospect of an
end to the long-term violations in the United Nations controlled
zone.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said these provide a constant irritant in the
relations between UNMOP and the local authorities, a irritant
which should be removed.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-General said UNMOP has played an essential role
in maintaining conditions conducive to negotiations, and recent
developments at other parts of the border between Croatia and
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia raise the hope that the two
countries can solve the disputed issue of Prevlaka through
mutual negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Secretary-General recommended a further
six-month extension of UNMOP mandate until July 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
UNMOP consists of 28 United Nations military observers headed
by a Chief Military Observer. The current mandate of the mission
expires on January 15, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Not to Seek Delay in Opening Border with Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany Monday denied that it wants
to delay implementing the open-border Schengen agreement with
Italy for fear that the Kurdish refugees who are streaming into
Italy from Turkey would finally slip into Germany.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of some 1,200 mostly Kurdish refugees in southern
Italian coast in the last two weeks has sparked growing alarm in
Europe, especially Germany, over a possible new immigration wave.
</P>
<P>
Police chiefs from France, Germany, Greece, Italy, the
Netherlands and Turkey are due to meet in Rome on Thursday to
discuss measures to stop the influx of Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the German Interior Ministry said that Germany
would press at the police conference for stricter adherence with
the Schengen agreement and tighter control of European external
borders.
</P>
<P>
Germany would not seek a temporary delay in implementing the
Schengen agreement under which the German-Italian border controls
would be phased out by this Spring, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, German Interior Minister Manfred Kanther
reiterated his call on Italy to tighten border controls and take
considerable tougher measures against illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Kanther also said that Germany had already reinforced police
forces at its southern border and would send back those immigrants
who slipped illegally into Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
