<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Limits Emissions to Reduce Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Himalayan kingdom of Nepal
has set the limits for vehicular emissions with a view to reducing
pollution in the country, particularly in the Kathmandu Valley,
the official RSS news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the limits set by the Transport Management Department,
emissions produced by four-wheel petrol-running vehicles
manufactured before 1980 should not contain more than 4.5 percent
of carbon monoxide and those manufactured after 1991 not more than
three percent.
</P>
<P>
Emissions by three wheelers and two wheelers manufactured after
1991 should not contain more than 4.5 percent of carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, emissions by diesel-running vehicles manufactured
before 1994 should not contain more than 75 smoke units and those
manufactured after 1995 not more than 65 units.
</P>
<P>
The limits will come into force from January 14 for four-wheel
vehicles and from mid-July for two wheelers.
</P>
<P>
Vehicular emissions, among others, are blamed for the
deteriorating environment in the Kathmandu Valley, which has the
lion's share of the vehicles in the country.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1998 has been designated as the Visit Nepal Year by
the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
