<HEADLINE> Bonn Rejects Greek Ruling for War Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany Monday rejected a Greek
court ruling which demands compensation for victims of a wartime
massacre carried out by German troops, the German press agency DPA
reported.
</P>
<P>
A parliament statement said Bonn will not recognize the verdict
of the Greek state court in Levadia, stressing the government
position that such court cases contradict the immunity of state
principle and are not permissible.
</P>
<P>
The Greek court decided that the German government should pay
60 million marks (33 million U.S. dollars) in compensation to the
families of people killed by German troops in a June 1944
massacre.
</P>
<P>
The government holds that questions of reparations should not
be justified 50 years after the end of the Second World War, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
A German court in Bonn last June rejected several demands by
Greek nationals for compensation for wartime events.  
</P>
</TEXT>
