<HEADLINE> Lebanese Speaker Says Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri said today that an Israeli proposal to withdraw its troops
from Lebanon is conditional, and therefore is "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Berri made the remark during his meeting with a visiting
U.S. delegation of congressmen. He said that the U.N. Security
Council resolution 425 stipulates that Israel unconditionally
withdraw its troops from south Lebanon and Bekaa valley.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai told an
Arabic language publication that his country was prepared to
implement the resolution provided agreement is reached with
Lebanon to meet Israel's security demands.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the past more than 10 years that
Israel officially accepted the resolution. On Sunday, a statement
from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office confirmed
the defense minister's comments.
</P>
<P>
Berri said that Netanyahu's proposal is not new as long as he
links withdrawal with any condition, adding that his pure purpose
is to separate the Syrian track in the Middle East peace talks
from the Lebanese track.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern border towns from across
border attacks. 
</P>
