<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Economy to Show Improvement in 1998: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' economy is expected to
show an improvement in 1998, with a good prospect for tourism on
the island.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey jointly conducted by Cyprus'
Planning Bureau, the Central Bank and weekly newspaper Financial
Mirror, bankers and economists forecast a growth rate of 4 to 4.5
percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rosy projections are based on the good performance of the
island's economy in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Cypriot Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou
said the economic growth rate has increased from one percent in
the first half of 1997 to 4 percent in the second half and is
expected to reach 4.5 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the revival of the economy which started in
May last year is steadily continuing with its main driving force
being tourism, offshore and other services sectors.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists visiting the island rose 8 percent for
the May-October period of last year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, one of the main sources of income for this island
nation, accounted for nearly 20 percent of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Most economists forecast that the total number of tourist
arrivals in 1998 will reach 2.1 million to 2.23 million, with
foreign exchange earnings climbing to 1.6 billion to 1.67 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With regard to other indicators, economists believe inflation
this year will be maintained at 1997 level and unemployment rate
will become slightly lower.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Christodoulou has said that inflation and
unemployment for 1997 would be estimated at 3.5 percent and 3.3
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Local economists, however, point out that good prospects for
Cyprus' economy will be based on the condition that there are no
adverse developments on the island in 1998.
</P>
<P>
They noted that there are some destabilizing factors in the new
year, including the arrival by mid-summer of the Russian-made
anti-aircraft missiles. Turkey has warned that it will launch a
preemptive strike to destroy them before they are deployed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
