<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Approves 1998 State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Despite of the deepening
crisis in the coalition government, Israeli Knesset (parliament)
today approved the 1998 state budget of 207 billion shekels
(about 59 billion U.S. dollars.)
</P>
<P>
In the final third reading of the budget, the coalition
defeated the opposition by a vote of 58 to 52, with one
abstention. And in the second reading early this afternoon, the
coalition also won all the votes on the accompanying arrangements
bill of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy, who submitted his resignation
Sunday and caused an earthquake in the political spectrum of
Israel, voted against the budget with three colleagues of his
Gesher party.
</P>
<P>
However, other coalition factions and Moledet party, whose
demands related to the budget have been met by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, today gave strong backing to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The vote on the budget, which should have been concluded on
December 31, 1997, was delayed in a bid to buy time for
Netanyahu to win the support of Levy by meeting his demands on
allocating more resources to the developing towns and
disadvantaged neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
Although Netanyahu failed to win Levy's support, he
successfully overcame the first hurdle today after his government
was seriously weakened by the departure of five-member Gesher
party, which left the coalition in a bare majority of 61 in
the 120-seat Knesset.
</P>
<P>
In response to Levy's resignation, Netanyahu said Sunday that
he is confident his government will survive the crisis and that
early elections will not be held.
</P>
<P>
But opposition Labor party leader Ehud Barak stressed today
before the budget vote that the Netanyahu government will collapse
in a matter of weeks and early elections will be held this
year. He added that Labor will call for a non-confidence motion
against Netanyahu next week.
</P>
<P>
It was widely believed that Netanyahu must do his best to
stabilize the coalition after today's vote so that his government
could survive the imminent crisis over the issue of second
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu today confirmed that the cabinet will work out a
detailed plan for the further withdrawal from the West Bank before
his scheduled meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton later this
month.
</P>
<P>
But it will be difficult for Netanuahu to maneuver between the
coalition, which will be dominated by extreme right wingers, and
the U.S. administration, which has reportedly pressed Israel to
withdraw no less than 10 percent of the West Bank in the further
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party, a faction in the coalition, today
stressed that if Netanyahu caves in to pressure and makes major
concessions to the Palestinians, it will topple the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
