<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Determined to Push Mideast Peace Process Forward: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it would continue to push the Middle East peace process
forward despite the resignation of Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process continues. This is a process about peace and
not about people," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters. "The U.S. government believes it needs to move forward
based on what it thinks is best, and not based on the particular
make-up of a particular government at a particular time."
</P>
<P>
Levy announced his decision to resign from the post of the
foreign minister Sunday because of a dispute with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over social policy and the peace
process. His move has left Netanyahu's Likud-led ruling coalition
to a one-vote majority in the Knesset, the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the departure of Levy, moderate and cooperative
in resolving outstanding issues for the Middle East peace process
in accordance with interim accords agreed between the Palestinians
and Israel's former Labor government, will strengthen the right
faction's force in the coalition government and further stall the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
But Washington seems determined to pull the peace process back
on track, which has been derailed since last March as a result of
Israel's unilateral decision to build Jewish housing units in
Arab's East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry earlier also expressed such
determination of the Clinton administration, saying Levy's quit
from the Israeli government would not affect the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Middle East peace process has always continued in its
sometimes measured way despite internal political developments
affecting the government of Israel," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"Individuals and the role individual cabinet members play in
the process change from time to time but the process continues,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said there had been political turmoil in the region
before and "we have still gone forward with trying to negotiate
and nudge and push for progress."
</P>
<P>
He stressed Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was convinced
that there is urgent need for progress in 1998 because in 1997
"there has been no forward movement" on peace.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross was set to leave for
the region later in the day for the preparation of President Bill
Clinton's separate meetings with Netanyahu on January 20 and with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat two days later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Slams PKK for Illegal Immigration Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today accused the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) of plotting the latest
illegal immigration to Europe, semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Turkish Interior Minister
Murat Baseskioglu said that the PKK attempted to tarnish Turkey's
reputation through the immigration tide.
</P>
<P>
"They are creating a false image that people are unable
to live in Turkey," Baseskioglu said, adding that this is a new
step adopted by the PKK following its military setbacks.
</P>
<P>
Large number of illegal immigrants from Turkey and northern
Iraq, through different ways, rushed recently to European
countries, especially Italy, causing grave concerns among the
European countries.
</P>
<P>
Baseskioglu said that the PKK wants to deceive money from
these illegal immigrants by irresponsibly promising them "a better
life" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting against the Turkish government in
southeastern Turkey for an independent state since 1984. The
Turkish government troops have been launching cross-border
operations in northern Iraq to destroy PKK bases in the region.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on Italy and other relevant European
countries not to grant these people political asylum, adding that
such a move will encourage the immigration flood.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that, to a certain extent, bad economic
situation in Turkey can also be termed as one of the reasons for
the illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at a weekly news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that these immigrants did not go to
Europe due to the alleged human rights reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody knows that these people are leaving Turkey in
search of a better life for themselves and their families. They
are not fleeing prosecution," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
Indicating that some European countries have a bias against
Turkey, Atacanli stressed that the current illegal immigration has
nothing to do with human rights.
</P>
<P>
European countries have always criticized Turkey for its poor
human rights record, saying that Turkey will not achieve its aim
of becoming a European Union member unless it makes a remarkable
improvement in this issue.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that as many as 1,200 people, mostly
Turks and Kurds from northern Iraq, were smuggled into Italy last
week.
</P>
<P>
As a country linking Asia and Europe, Turkey has been a main
springboard for the illegal immigration from some poor Asian
countries to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
