<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Issues New Emergency Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese Ministry of
Justice issued today a law on the state of emergency and
safeguarding of public safety, which was approved last week by
Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
According to Undersecretary of State for Justice Shawki
Hussein, the new emergency law deals with cases where the Sudanese
president is empowered to proclaim a state of emergency throughout
the country or in any region.
</P>
<P>
These cases include foreign invasion or siege, such as the
current embargo, that may threaten national unity and safety, and
crises that threaten the country's economy, such as rebellion,
illegal fighting, insurrection, rioting and natural upheavals.
</P>
<P>
The new law abolishes the 1939 law on the defense of Sudan
which has been in effect ever since the colonial era. The Ministry
of Justice is drafting regulations for enforcing the new
law, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the new law has given further power
to the Sudanese president to declare the state of emergency under
diverse circumstances without arousing any debate or opposition on
the part of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In fact, al-Bashir's declaration of a state of emergency in
west Sudan last December to counter armed robberies has given rise
to heated debates among Sudanese parliamentarians about its
effectiveness and repercussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
