<HEADLINE> U.S. Donates 29 Million Dlrs for Ex-Yugoslavia Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
today that it will contribute 29 million U.S. dollars to the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to support its
activities in Bosnia, Croatia, Serbian and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by James Rubin, a spokesman for the
State Department, at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"Because most refugees and displaced persons in the region come
from areas where their ethnic groups are minorities, the UNHCR
will concentrate on overcoming obstacles to return across ethnic
lines," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government works closely with UNHCR and other
humanitarian organizations to facilitate repatriation, monitor the
safety of refugees and displaced persons," he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Rubin said the U.S. is pleased to note that the
multiethnic police force in the northern Bosnian town of Brcko
began patrolling today.
</P>
<P>
The new development came out of a decree issued by Brcko
Supervisor Bill Ferrand about two months ago that called for a
reorganized, integrated force to be functional by the first of the
year.
</P>
<P>
"We are very pleased with today's beginning, and it's part of
an ongoing effort at reintegrating Brcko," added Rubin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
