<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reforms Breathes Life into South China Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, has scored remakable achievements in
reforms in State-owned enterprises, especially in the introduction
of a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou Mayor Lin Shusen made the remarks today at the
opening of a work conference on local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The city generated 163 billion yuan in industrial output value
in the January-November period last year, up 14 percent on
the same 1996 period, with the sales-production ratio reaching 96
percent, according to Lin.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium-sized state enterprises, which contributed
close to 50 percent of the local industrial output value, have
been given a new lease on life through the optimal reorganization
of sources, said Lin.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 key enterprise groups in the city have been authorized
to manage their state assets and 46 others have been approved to
establish subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
One third of some 400 small state enterprises have restructured
their management systems.
</P>
<P>
The city was home to some 4,000 shareholder companies by November
1997, up 18 percent on the 1996 period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
