<HEADLINE> India, Italy Sign Agreement on Combating Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua)-- India and Italy Tuesday signed
an agreement on cooperation in combating terrorism, organized
crime and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed visiting Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi and his Indian counterpart Inder Kumar Gujral held official
talks on a wide range of bilateral and global issues including the
United Nations reforms, official sources said here.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who arrived here Tuesday morning on a three-day visit to
India, also called on Indian President K. R. Narayanan and
Vice-President Krishna Kant and exchanged views with them on
bilateral relations and matters of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
A cultural exchange program was also signed to strengthen the
close contact between India and Italy. The two sides would also
sign a memorandum of understanding on bilateral cooperation in
small and medium-sized enterprises, during Prodi's visit to
Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu in southern India on Thursday, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Italian prime minister made a speech on
Indo-Italian relations at a seminar organized by the Rajiv Gandhi
Foundation here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
