<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Marks Centenary of Milestone Letter by Zola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- France plans to mark the centenary
of a protest letter by writer Emile Zola in which he defended a
Jewish officer wrongly condemned for treason.
</P>
<P>
Zola published the letter, entitled "J'accuse" in French, in
the newspaper L`Aurore on January 13, 1898.
</P>
<P>
The letter, addressed to the then French President Felix Faure,
reveals what now known as "Dreyfus Affair," actually one of the
biggest anti-Semitic scandals of the French army.
</P>
<P>
In what was called the "most revolutionary act of the century"
by France's socialist founding father Jean Jaures, Zola protested
the persecution against Jewish captain Alfred Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
Dreyfus was stripped of military status, wrongly condemned by a
military tribunal for spying for the Germans, and exiled to the
French Guyana. He was rehabilitated in 1906, but his innocence was
not fully recognized by the army until 1930.
</P>
<P>
On the upcoming January 12, French President Jacques Chirac
will reveal a plaque on a house in the ninth district of Paris, in
which Zola wrote the letter, lived and died.
</P>
<P>
The National Library of France is scheduled to exhibit the
original copy of the letter and several other authentic documents
on the Dreyfus Affair.
</P>
<P>
A series of debates, seminars and ceremonies will be organized
by the Ministry of National Education, the Sorbonne University and
the Ministry of Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
