<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Memorial Hall Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Qiu Hongbiao, a 43-year-old
businessman from the city of Shenzhen in southern Guangdong
Province, arrived at Tiananmen Square in the center of the
Chinese Capital this morning much earlier than most other visitors.
</P>
<P>
Qiu journeyed to Beijing to realize his long-cherished dream of
being in the presence of Chairman Mao.
</P>
<P>
Qiu made a special trip to Beijing last month, but the memorial
hall did not reopen, and he returned in despair.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't have the opportunity to see Chairman Mao personally
when he was alive," said Qiu, "and now my wish comes true."
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 visitors, mostly from other parts of the
country, braved this morning's bone chilling winds to queue in
front of the Memorial Hall for the late Chinese leader Mao
Zedong. The throng gathered to await the reopening of the hall
following a nine-month maintenance project.
</P>
<P>
The base of the white jade statue of Mao was awash with fresh
flowers shortly after the hall opened.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the Great Leader rest peacefully in a crystal
coffin covered with a flag of the Communist Party of
China. Visitors silently viewed Mao's face and often their eyes
welled tears.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 5,000 people visited the hall in the first hour
after its reopening, including a septuagenarian couple -- Sheng
Hebang and his wife -- from central China's Henan Province. The
couple reportedly flew in here Monday for the sole purpose of
visiting the Mao memorial.
</P>
<P>
"I've followed late Chairman Mao for all my life and I love him
very much," said the old man, "We will never forget his loving
kindness."
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall was completed in May 1977 and opened to the
public on September 9, 1977, on the first anniversary of Mao's
death.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110 million people had visited the sacred memorial
by March 28, 1997, when its administrative authorities announced
that the hall would be closed for renovations from April 1 to
December 31, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
