<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard to Offer 799-dollar PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett-Packard (HP) Co.,
one of the largest U.S. computer makers, said Monday it would
offer Intel-based multimedia personal computers at 799 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This is the lowest price point we have ever hit at
introduction," said Webb Mckinney, the California-based company's
General Manager of the Home Products Division.
</P>
<P>
It's also the lowest price for such product in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
HP's 799-dollar model, known as Pavilion 3260, is designed
around a 200-megahertz Pentium processor from Intel, together with
embedded multimedia technology and 32 megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say the battle to capture home buyers of
personal computers will heat up with HP launching a 799-dollar
system on the eve of an annual trade show hosted by the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturing Association in Las Vegas later this week.
</P>
<P>
Computer systems priced below 1,000 dollars made up 7.2 percent
of the desktop units sold by U.S. retailers in the beginning of
1997, but jumped to 32.2 percent by the end of the year, according
to Computer Intelligence, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe similar price cuts may be announced in the
next two days by other large computer makers, such as Compaq
Computer Corp. and IBM, before they exhibit their new products in
Las Vegas, where a "price war" seems inevitable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
