<HEADLINE> Central Asian Countries Air Views on Regional Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of five central
Asian countries on Tuesday exchanged views on the formation of a
regional union at a summit meeting in Ashgabat, capital of
Turkmenistan, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The heads of Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan
and Kyrgyzstan unanimously agreed that "each member of the
Commonwealth (CIS) should determine its participation
independently on the basis of domestic priorities and
international commitments."
</P>
<P>
Turkmen President Saparmurad Niyazov said his country was a
neutral state which can be a member of such organizations
"exclusively as an observer."
</P>
<P>
Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov said that his country was
prepared to become a full member of the Central Asian Union.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement issued after the summit said it
"contributed to verifying positions on key issues of relations
between the five brotherly republics." 
</P>
