<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonists Postpone Round World Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Two American balloonists, who
planned to start today their attempt to circle the globe by taking
a balloon without stop, decided to postpone their takeoff because
of wind problem over the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The jet stream that would have carried Dick Rutan and partner
Dave Melton across the ocean were waning and the winds around
Albuquerque were unsettled, the crew's weather forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
The launch was postponed for 10 days to two weeks and the crew
was to meet today to reassess their plan.
</P>
<P>
"You work for months to get to this point, then a few hours
before you plan to take off you're delayed -- of course we're
upset," Melton said this morning.
</P>
<P>
"It's a letdown, but we know we'll have another try at it,"
Melton said.
</P>
<P>
The crew estimated that the jet stream would slow the balloon
down by at least two days, but they expected the disruption would
pass in about 10 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
