<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 percent S. Korean Companies to Cut Labor Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 40 percent of South Korean
companies are planning to cut their manpower due to the current
financial crisis, said a survey issued by the Korea Chamber of
Commerce and Industry Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 39.8 percent of the surveyed 376 companies and banking
institutions said they are planning to slow down their operations
while 42.5 percent said they will curtail personnel by up to 100,
and 15 percent is to cut at least 300.
</P>
<P>
Of the surveyed, 92.3 percent consented the need of workforce
reduction while 63.6 percent will opt for a smaller paycheck as
part of downsizing.
</P>
<P>
But, observers said reality will be more harsh as South Korean
financial institutions will have to go through painstaking
economic restructuring, including massive layoffs, since the
current financial crisis simply can not be solved through more
borrowing.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that the crisis caused by failure of
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions, will
further deepen if the country failed to attract substantial
foreign investment in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
This year, they said, will be surely worse than the previous
year for the nation, once the 11th largest economy in the world,
in many respects -- inflation and unemployment will rise and more
bankruptcies are expected to take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
