<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.74 Million People Shake Off Poverty in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- About 1.74 million
poverty-stricken people in southwest China's Guizhou province
shook off poverty last year.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial government said that so far 70
percent of the poverty-stricken people in Guizhou have got rid of
poverty. Guizhou is one of the poorest provinces in China.
</P>
<P>
Due to the development of infrastructure in Guizhou, the
average annual net income of farmers reached 1,298 yuan in 1997,
up 4.2 percent on 1996. The poverty-stricken population
in the province reduced from ten million in 1993 to 4.55 million
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 18 more townships in Guizhou were connected with
roads, 35 equipped with power facilities, 25 with telephones, and
350 satellite ground stations built to receive TV and radio
programs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Guizhou helped the poor by encouraging them to
transform low-yield land into high-yield fields. Various training
courses were held for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has also built many poverty-relief projects and
production bases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Institute Tunes Down German Growth Projection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A leading German economic research
institute said Tuesday that Germany's economy would grow by only
2.5 percent in 1998 instead of an early projection of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic report, the Berlin-based German
Institute for Economic Research DIW also said that Germany's gross
domestic product (GDP) would increase by only 2.2 percent in 1997
compared with the government forecast of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, unemployment in Germany is set to continue rising in
1998, with the average jobless total expected to climb to 4.51
million from 4.39 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The institute also put Germany's budget deficit in 1997 at 3.3
percent of GDP, thus missing the European Union Maastricht Treaty
target of 3.0 percent of GDP required for qualification for the
single European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
However, Germany would be able to reduce its budget deficit to
2.7 percent of GDP in 1998, the DIW said.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that the German mark would continue to lose
value against the U.S. dollar in 1998. But the pace of
depreciation is likely to slow down during the course of the
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Situation Severe in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- With almost no operational
quarantines, the cholera situation in the Somali capital here is
alarming as the death rate is increasing by the day.
</P>
<P>
Local health authorities declared a state of emergency
following the spread of the disease to all sectors of the
community in the capital and elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
In last week alone, more than 60 cases of death were reported
due to poorly equipped health facilities in both sides of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Benadir Hospital, the only operational quarantine and the
largest cholera recipient facility in Mogadishu is accommodating
more than 630 cholera patients and a total of 19 deaths had been
reported, four of which died this morning.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of new cholera victims are still pouring into the
hospital which can no longer cope with the overwhelming number of
cholera patients.
</P>
<P>
Dr Abdirizak Hassan Ali, director of Benadir Hospital, told
Xinhua today that they are running short of medical supplies.
According to Dr Ali, the local Islamic organization, the Moslem
Solidarity Forum, and the International Committee of the Red
Cross are offering insufficient donations to the cholera victims.
</P>
<P>
He added that the hospital can't conduct the necessary
treatments after dark owing to the lack of fuel for the
generators on the premises.
</P>
<P>
Dr Osman Mohamud Dufle, coordinator of the Joint Health
Authority in Mogadishu, said the cholera patients are now
scattered throughout the capital, causing more hazards to the
community.
</P>
<P>
Dr Dufle noted that the spread of the disease has resulted
from the lack of quarantines, malnutrition and the poor
sanitation in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
"More than 20 percent of the cholera patients are dying," he
said, adding, "the European Union brought about 500 cartons of
infusion and the essential drugs against the cholera, but no
distribution is being made unless the international aid agencies
arrive in the capital."
</P>
<P>
It is not in the capital alone where the cholera epidemic is
tightening its grip. Six deaths are reported from Balad
district, 30 km North of Mogadishu this week. And more than 37
cholera and severe cerebral malaria deaths are reported in
Dhanawe village of Bakol region.
</P>
<P>
Both Dr Dufle and Dr Ali agreed that the security situation in
the capital is relatively Okay to allow the aid agencies to
operate. And the local health authority is appealing for the
return of the international aid agencies to help tackle the
desperate cholera situation.
</P>
<P>
Water borne diseases such as cholera, yellow fever and malaria
are claiming lives throughout the country which has no central
authority for the seventh year now since the overthrow of former
President S. Barre in 1991 plunged the country into tribal war.
</P>
<P>
The Somalis are expecting the formation of a government of
national unity in the first half of this year following the
agreement reached recently by the Somali factions in Cairo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
