<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Veteran Revolutionary Cremated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Veteran Chinese communist Liu
Lantao passed away on December 31 at the age of 88 and his remains
were cremated today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
No ceremonial activities were conducted and the remains were
disposed of in accordance with Liu's will.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders including Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Zhu
Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Liu Huaqing, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing, Li
Lanqing, Rong Yiren and Ding Guangen visited Liu during his stay
in hospital, and paid condolences to his relatives following his
death.
</P>
<P>
Liu was a dedicated fighter for the cause of communism and a
veteran proletarian revolutionary, as well as an eminent official
in charge of Party affairs of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
and the affairs of the Party's United Front.
</P>
<P>
Liu was born into a poor family in Mizhi County, northwest
China's Shaanxi province, in November 1910. He joined the
Communist Youth League of China in 1926 and the CPC in 1928.
</P>
<P>
Active in CPC revolutionary movements and battles against the
ruling Kuomintang Regime and Japanese aggressors, Liu was arrested
twice and imprisoned by the Kuomintang between 1930-1936.
</P>
<P>
He mainly worked in north China between 1936-1954, and was one
of the major senior CPC officials in the area between 1948-1954.
</P>
<P>
After 1955, Liu held numerous major positions related to the
internal affairs and international affairs of the CPC, as well as
local affairs in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
Liu was persecuted by the Gang of Four during the turmoil of
the "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
He worked mainly for the United Front sector following 1979,
serving first as deputy head of the CPC Central Committee United
Front Department and then as vice-chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Liu was elected a member of the CPC Central Committee during
the Fourth Plenary Session of the 11th CPC Central Committee, and
subsequently served as a member of the Standing committee of the
CPC Central Advisory Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Communist Daily Publishes Evidence on Crime of Papon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The French Communist Party's daily
"L`Humanite" used 11 pages in its Tuesday issue to publish
documents which can serve as evidence to prove the anti-Semitic
crimes of former Vichy official Maurice Papon.
</P>
<P>
Papon, 87, has been standing trial since last October in the
Assize Court of Bordeaux in the Gironde Prefecture, southwest
France, over charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of deporting 6,900 Jews, including many
children, from Gironde to Nazi death camps from 1942 to 1944, when
he was number two of the government of Gironde under the Vichy
collaboration regime.
</P>
<P>
One of the document published by "L`Humanite" was a letter by
the chief of Gestapo in France to the prefectural government of
Gironde, asking the latter to arrest the Communist resistance
fighters in aviation factories of the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Another letter, dated July 10, 1943, informed Papon a planned
visit to Bordeaux by the general commissioner in charge of the
Jewish files of the Vichy regime, Louis Darquier de Pellepoix.
</P>
<P>
Another letter, dated July 7, 1944, which was after Paris was
liberated, and signed by the chief of the prefectural government
of Gironde Jean Chapel, ordered the arrest of nine Frenchmen.
</P>
<P>
Papon has denied that he master-minded the deportation of the
Jews and instead claimed that he had done his best to save the
lives of Jews and had been engaged in resistance movements against
the Germans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
