<HEADLINE> Chechen Kidnapers Demand Ransom for Release of Poles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Chechen kidnapers reportedly
demanded a ransom of 3 million U.S. dollars for the release of
five Polish aid workers held hostage since December 17.
</P>
<P>
Media reports published here Tuesday said the ransom demand was
confirmed by Mohamed Mohamedov, deputy chief of the anti-terrorist
center in Chechnya, a republic of Russia.
</P>
<P>
However, in the region's capital of Grozny, a representative
for the Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe said he
knew nothing about the latest development.
</P>
<P>
Mohamedov said the five Poles working for a Polish-Chechen
friendship society were safe and sound, and the Polish government
should never agree to pay the ransom.
</P>
<P>
The aid workers were held hostage by a dozen armed gangsters
and the whereabouts of the abducted were unclear because they were
often taken from one place to another, he added.
</P>
<P>
Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said the five young
men were abducted some 30 kilometers west of Grozny, where their
minibus was found with its tires shot out.
</P>
<P>
Moscow said some 800 people had been held hostage over the past
year in the region, which fought a bloody war for full
independence from Russia during 1994-1996.
</P>
<P>
After the war, terrorism reigns the region and armed gangs
often surface to kidnap foreigners for ransom money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
