<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall in Tokyo on Poor Economic Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo Stocks continued to fall
Tuesday, the second day of new year trading, amid lingering
pessimism over the sluggish Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
at the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which dropped 301.90 points Monday,
lost 60.44 points more, or 0.40 percent, to close at 14,896.40.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, which
covers all issues on the First Section, fell 5.98 points, or 0.51
percent, to close at 1,160.65.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 350 million
shares, up from Monday's 156.62 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Collapsed Yamaichi Securities Co. was Tuesday's most actively
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
During the morning session, the Nikkei index tumbled below
14,775.22, the 1997 low marked on December 29, with heavy
arbitrage unwinding triggered by the major depreciation of the yen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency briefly climed to the 134 yen level in Tokyo
for the first time since April 1992.
</P>
<P>
Deterioration of Asian currencies such as Thai baht, the
Malaysian ringgit and the Indonesian rupiah also dampened the
market sentiment, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo market was briefly buoyed in the early afternoon by
news that the Finance Ministry will announce later in the day a
set of measures to shore up the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced gainers 738 to 341, with 141 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
