<HEADLINE> Top Ten Medical Science, Technology Stories for 1997  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Health announced
here today the top ten '97 news stories on Chinese medical science
and technology, with the No.1 story covering "the development of
three inactive vaccines for the treatment of epidemic hemorrhagic
fever."
</P>
<P>
And the No.2 story covered the cloning of the gene for typical
hereditary diseases.
</P>
<P>
The remaining stories included:
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese doctors made major progress in their researches
related to pathogenic mechanisms for treating burn victims in the
early stages and in the ensuing healing process. Their research
provided new methods for the clinical treatment of burns and an
increase in the recovery rate.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese experts recorded notable breakthrough when applying
gene therapy to the treatment of hereditary disease. Related
therapy led to the recovery of four patients suffered from
hemophilia, the world's only reported cases of recovery from the
disease.
</P>
<P>
-- In the realm of neurosurgery, three-dimensional
micro-surgery technology was further developed and robots were
introduced to the surgical procedures.
</P>
<P>
-- the HBV (Hepatitis B Virus) strain was developed in
rats. Chinese scientists discovered the special distribution
principles of HCV in China, and substantial progress was made in
the research and manufacture of new-type elements for the
rejuvenation of human live cells.
</P>
<P>
-- Large-scale and extensive efforts to modernize Chinese
traditional medicine as an industry were introduced.
</P>
</TEXT>
