<HEADLINE> France Attributes Exodus of Kurds to Anarchy in N. Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement Tuesday attributed the exodus of Kurds
toward Europe to the lack of government in northern Iraq since the
end of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"If the northern part of Iraq had not been turned into a no
man's land... perhaps there would not be the influx of Kurds that
we are seeing," said Chevenement after holding a meeting with
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on the issue Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that since the end of the Gulf War, northern
Iraq has been subjected to all kinds of attacks, invasions and
civil wars among different factions of the Kurds and between
Kurdish forces and the government forces of Turkey and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problem of Kurds did not come out "by hazard"
and is linked with other problems such as criminal immigration
trafficking networks working in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed Turkey for allowing the Kurds being smuggled out
of its coast by mafias.
</P>
<P>
"I think that when a boat quits the Turkish coast, they should
see it," he said,
</P>
<P>
The general directors of police force from several principal
European countries concerned with the Kurdish exodus, including
Turkey, will meet in Rome on Thursday to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
A boat carrying about 900 Kurds arrived in Italy from Turkey in
December, while thousands of others are trying to illegally enter
European countries through other routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
