<HEADLINE> 1,249 Killed in Highway Mishaps in Bangladesh in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- As many as 1,249 people were
killed and 16,000 others wounded in road accidents on two highways
in Bangladesh last year, said local press reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the 208-kilometer-long highway linking Dhaka and Sylhel,
northeast of the capital city, at least 959 people were killed and
12,000 others injured in 1997 in road accidents.
</P>
<P>
More than 290 people were killed and 4,000 others injured in
320 accidents on the 80-kilometer-long highway between Dhaka and
Aricha, northwest of the capital, in the same year.
</P>
<P>
The two highways are the busiest routes in the country. Many
of the vehicles running on the two roads are over-loaded, and the
roads' bad condition worsens the traffic situation, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The reports attributed the high rates of accidents and
casualties to vehicle overloading, reckless and licenseless
driving, and faulty vehicles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
