<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy has formally quit his post before his resignation takes
effect later today, 48 hours after he tendered the resignation
letter to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Levy bode farewell to the ministry staff and workers in a
formal ceremony held at the Foreign Ministry. His resignation
will go into effect at 7:30 p.m.(local time) today.
</P>
<P>
He said that he could not remain in the current coalition
government led by Likud Party, because he came to the conclusion
that he no longer makes impact. He added that he hoped the
government would be able to correct its ways during this
difficult time.
</P>
<P>
Levy dropped a political bombshell to the country when he
announced his resignation, citing the failure of the government
to tackle worsening social problems and push forward the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the parliamentary vote for the 1998 Budget Monday, Levy and
four members of his Gesher Party voted with the opposition against
the budget in protest against the government's policy of cutting
welfare benefits to the poor population.
</P>
<P>
Levy, a veteran politician who has served in several Likud
governments, has long been a political arch-rival with current
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Their deeply-rooted feud
originated from the 1993 battle for the Likud leadership, during
which Netanyahu defeated Levy.
</P>
<P>
The feud led to Levy's departure from the Likud to create the
Gesher Party in early 1996 before the general elections in May
that year. But following the mediation of Likud's veteran Ariel
Sharon, currently Infrastructure Minister, Levy agreed to reunite
with the Likud to attend the elections, helping sweep Netanyahu
to power.
</P>
<P>
Since assuming office in the foreign ministry, Levy had
already threatened to resign for five times before the Sunday
announcement because he felt repeatedly being sidelined by
Netanyahu in the decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
Levy's leave has pushed the Netanyahu government into a
survival crisis by reducing its majority in the 120-seat Knesset
(Parliament) to the minimal 61 seats needed to keep going. This
has fueled the speculation that the coalition could collapse at
any time soon, leading to new elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
