<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Launches Biggest Drainage Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Tuesday launched
its biggest ever drainage project in Punjab's provincial capital
of Lahore, which is aimed at minimizing drainage surplus, the
Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
The government's incentive policies for the agriculture sector
can not bear fruit if the land remains afflicted with water
logging and salinity, Minister for Water and Power Raja Nadir
Pervaiz said at the launching ceremony for the 713 million-U.S.
dollar project.
</P>
<P>
Co-financed by the Pakistani federal and provincial
governments, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank, the
project is expected to evacuate all saline drainable surpluses
from the Indus Basin, which covers the provinces of Punjab and
Sindh and parts of Balochistan and the North West Frontier
Province.
</P>
<P>
Pervaiz said the performance of the agriculture sector had a
strong bearing on the national economic planning as it accounts
for more than 25 percent of the Gross Domestic Product.
</P>
<P>
The irrigated farm land, which accounts for about 80 percent of
the total cropped area of the country, has been threatened by
water-logging and salinity for almost 40 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, a number of drainage projects have been set up
to control water-logging and salinity, but the performance of
these projects has been below expectations mainly because of poor
management.
</P>
<P>
The country's drainage system is seriously handicapped with a
host of problems like accumulation of incoming salts and the
continued incidence of water logging and salinity, according to
the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Poisoning Rises in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain saw a record number of
food poisonings in 1997 with the annual figure passing 100,000 for
the first time, the New Scientist magazine reported.
</P>
<P>
The total incidence of food poisoning last year is seven times
as high as 15 years ago. Up to 200 people may have died from what
they ate, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
However, these are only the reported cases. Richard Gilbert, an
expert at the Public Health Laboratory Service (PHLS) in London,
said that the figure should be multiplied by ten to reach a true
estimate.
</P>
<P>
"So it's probably closer to 1 million." Gilbert, PHLS's head of
food safety policy development, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rise of food poisoning in Britain has several causes and
changes in lifestyle is one to blame, said Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
More people now eat out than before, and consumers prefer fresh
produce, which is more likely to be contaminated if poorly stored
or handled at any point.
</P>
<P>
Consumers have also pressed for the elimination of
preservatives and other additives which used to keep bacteria out
of food.
</P>
<P>
To clean up the nation's food, strict targets should be set by
the government for the reduction of bacteria in poultry and better
hygiene is required throughout the food chain, Gilbert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
