<HEADLINE> S. Korea, IMF Readjust Agreed Macro Economic Indicators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the International
Monetary Fund have started to revise agreed macro economic
indicators, including the GDP growth rate, due to great financial
changes in the country, said the Ministry of Finance and Economy
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, South Korea signed an agreement with the IMF for a
rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars. Under the agreement with
stiff conditions, the nation has to completely restructure its
economy, open its financial market, close its ailing commercial
and merchant banks and companies, and cut its budget.
</P>
<P>
The agreed indicators were decided on a basis of the exchange
rate of one South Korean won against 1,100 dollars and yearly
interest rate of about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry pointed out that South Korea has to
change the indicators as the exchange rate now hovers around 1,650
won and interest rates exceed 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth rate is expected to be revised to about 1.5
percent in the aftermath of tightened monetary policy and the
restructuring of banking institutions imposed by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The increase rate of consumer price would be adjusted to roughly
7 percent from previous 5 percent while the unemployment rate to 5
percent from the previous projection of 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The readjustment will be finished Wednesday and will be sent to
the IMF board for consideration, according to the ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
