<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian currency, the
rupiah, hit a record low of 7,700 against the U.S. dollar Tuesday,
dealers here said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah reached 7,700 per dollar at the morning trading
session before closing the day at 7,350 per dollar. The drastic
drop of the rupiah was caused by weakness in regional currencies
and continuing local corporate demand for the dollar, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian currency has dropped by more than 200 percent
against the greenback from 2,361 per dollar in early July.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Malaysian ringgit also slid to 4.33 against
the dollar from 4.055 on Monday while the Thai baht plummeted to
54 per dollar from 42.65 and the Philippine peso to its lowest
level of 44.35 per dollar from 42.65.
</P>
<P>
Many economic analysts here blamed indebted corporations for
the sharp depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar. The
government has said Indonesia's private offshore debts total 65
billion dollars, accounting for 55 percent of the country's total
debts of 118 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Out of the private debts, 10 billion dollars will mature at the
beginning of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
