<HEADLINE> Congolese Refugees Faced with Starvation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIGALI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Congolese refugees who have
been relocated to a new site in Byumba in the northeast of Rwanda
are faced with problems of hunger and various diseases, Rwanda
Television (TVR) has reported.
</P>
<P>
"One Congolese refugee died on Sunday," a TVR crew that had
visited the estimated 16,000 ethnic Tutsi Congolese refugees at
Kageyo makeshift camp, near Byumba town had indicated.
</P>
<P>
The refugees themselves accused the UN Refugee Agency and
other humanitarian organizations of not providing them with
proper food and medical care.
</P>
<P>
"That information is baseless," claimed the UNHCR
Representative to Rwanda, Roman Urasa. "That crew never contacted
the authorities in Byumba, it only spoke to refugees."
</P>
<P>
Urasa indicated that UNHCR, in collaboration with the Rwanda
Red Cross distributed food rations for two weeks to refugees
before they left the north of Rwanda on December 22, 1997 for
Byumba.
</P>
<P>
"Each refugee receives the standard ration of 2,100 kcal per
day, we cannot change it," Urasa underlined. These rations are
made of maize, beans, and vegetable oil, he said.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Byumba have blamed the food shortages
in the camp to the fact that the refugees prefer to exchange food
relief with local commodities which are extremely expensive.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, what they gain in this bargaining is not enough
to cover the two week period between two distributions," they
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The decision to relocate Congolese refugees was taken
following two bloody attacks by Hutu extremists on Mudende
refugee camp, in Gisenyi, that claimed more than one thousand
lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
