<HEADLINE> Vanda, Walker Join Hands in Tapping China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong-based Vanda, a
pioneer in China's computer market, will forge partnership with
the American software developer Walker to capture market demand
stemming from the reform of Chinese state-owned enterprises (SOEs).
</P>
<P>
Vanda-Walker, the new joint venture, will be set up in Beijing,
providing state-of-the-art financial software solutions for Chinese
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
With the ongoing reform of SOEs, "we have identified further
business opportunities in the area of corporate financial
management, where the enterprises are compelled to make a major
effort to meet international standards," Edmund Ma, group managing
director of Vanda Systems and Communications Holdings Ltd., told
a joint press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Advanced financial software packages would be of major benefit
to these enterprises as they try to restructure and improve their
financial and general business performance, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Vanda holds a 45 percent share in the joint venture with Walker
holding the balance. The total investment value is 12 million HK
dollars (1.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1982, Vanda is one of the earliest system
integrators and computer suppliers on the China's inland. Its
customer base consists of major banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Walker specializes in business software and financial
solutions. Founded in 1969 and headquartered in San Francisco,
Walker is currently the largest supplier in the U.S. financial
software market for mainframe platforms, and its clientele
includes over 450 of the Fortune 1000 multi-nationals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
