<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De Bruin, Pankratov Lead Absentees from Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, Australia, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A long list of famous
absentees is certain to take some gloss off the world swimming
championships which is to open tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
After injuries forced Russian double Olympic champion Dennis
Pankratov out of the 11-day event, Michelle De Bruin, Ireland's
triple Olympic gold medalist, opted out too.
</P>
<P>
The no-shows also included local hero Kieren Perkins, holder of
three world records, flamboyant American Gary Hall, Jr., U.S.
Swimming's 1997 Swimmer of the Year, Chad Carvin, and Australia's
double Olympic silver medalist Scott Miller.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin, who stunned the world with her victories in the
women's 400-meter freestyle and 200- and 400-meter individual
medley events in the Atlanta Olympic Games, withdrew late December
from the Perth Worlds because of whiplash injuries sustained from
a car accident on October 31.
</P>
<P>
Smith said on December 22 that it was "pure heartbreak" to miss
the championships.
</P>
<P>
"I am disappointed because I might miss out on a chance of
going for a world championship title as the next world
championships is not until 2001," said Smith, 28.
</P>
<P>
Pankratov chose to skip the world championships because he
wanted to take a break.
</P>
<P>
The Russian won the 100- and 200-meter butterfly titles at the
Atlanta Games but swam poorly in the Euroean championships last
August. After a talk with his coach Viktor Avdeyenko, he decided
to have a rest.
</P>
<P>
In the European championships, Pankratov finished sixth in his
defence of his 100 meters title and failed to make the final of
the 200, an event in which he was unbeaten in major competition
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
"This (pulling out of the World) was a joint decision,"
Avdeyenko was quoted as saying last November.
</P>
<P>
Perkins, the holder of three freestyle world records, missed
out the world championships because of his own fault.
</P>
<P>
He finished third over 1,500 meters, the distance which has won
him two Olympic gold medals, finished fifth over 400 and failed to
reach the 200-meter final at the Australian world championship
trials last October.
</P>
<P>
Perkins ruled himself only 85 percent fit coming into the
trials after an eventful year, including marriage and the birth of
his daughter Georgia Jane last November.
</P>
<P>
Hall, Jr., the Olympic runner-up in both 50- and 100-meter
freestyle, is the other big name who flunked in the world
championship trials. The American who likes trash-talk and has a
hot temper failed to qualify for any individual event here and
will only compete in the 4x100 meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
Carvin, who won four events the U.S. nationals, was forced out
of the Perth Worlds by a bulging disc in his lower back that has
bothered him since the world championship trials last July.
</P>
<P>
The injury is yet another setback for Carvin, who had been
troubled by cardiomyopathy, a serious disease that kept him from
the 1996 Olympic trials. In 1994, days after competing in the Rome
world championships, he had his appendix removed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
