<HEADLINE> China Announces New List of Licensed Commodities for Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation has announced that 115 kinds of
export products will be subject to licensing administration in
1998.
</P>
<P>
A recent circular issued by the ministry notes that global
export licensing administrative procedures will be applied to all
related products.
</P>
<P>
Licenses for 21 types of commodities will be issued by the
Quota and License Administration Bureau, with licenses for 50
commodities issued by MOFTEC'S special commissioner's office and
another 62 by issuing authorities at the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
Effective January 1, 1998, export licensing requirements were
lifted for Chinese sorghum, while silicon carbide and
newsprint were added to the list of goods subject to licensing
controls.
</P>
<P>
Export quota bidding will be carried out for exports of
newsprint, according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
Exports of silicon carbide to the United States will be handled
by six import and export companies in Qinghai, Guizhou, Shaanxi
and Hainan provinces, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region. Other companies will be prohibited from engaging in
related business activities,
</P>
<P>
In addition, effective Jan 1, licenses for exports of wooden
pencils and vitamin C will be issued by MOFTEC's special
commissioner's offices, rather than by issuing authorities at the
provincial level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
