<HEADLINE> 160 Civilians Massacred in Latest Violence in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 160 people were
massacred over the past two days in western Algeria by Islamic
militants, adding the number of people killed since the beginning
of Ramadan to more than 500, said reports from Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates said that 117 people were killed from
Saturday night to Sunday in Meknassa in the region of Relizane in
western Algeria, while 43 others were killed in attacks upon
villages by Islamists.
</P>
<P>
The killing, accompanied with acts of barbarity, is taking on a
character of systematic extermination of inhabitants of whole
villages, and is reaching a climax without precedent since Algeria
plunged into violence six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Although the Algerian authorities remained silent over the
latest killings, the press called the massacres "genocide" and
said that the houses of the "gourbis," or people of misery, are
being destroyed on a daily base while men, women and babies had
their throats cut, burnt alive or mutilated.
</P>
<P>
Reports also said that whole villages, sometimes whole tribes,
are fleeing the areas they live for the centers of government
administration where it is safer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
