<HEADLINE> Leading Drug Companies Win Priority for Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A number of profitable hi-tech
enterprises will be selected as the future leaders of China's
giant pharmaceutical industry, a sector which is still in great
need of new drug and technology development, according to the
State Pharmaceutical Administration of China (SPAC).
</P>
<P>
The selection process will rank the top 50 of some 3,300
pharmaceutical enterprises for 1997, and will grant priorities for
technical renovations, research and development, stock listings
and foreign trade in order to sharpen their competitive edge in
both the domestic and international markets, according SPAC
Director Zheng Xiaoyu.
</P>
<P>
The firms, which mainly produce key basic pharmaceuticals, are
expected to contribute at least 60 percent of total annual sales
for the sector by the year 2000. Projections call for the top five
firms to earn 60 billion yuan (7.2 billion US dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Zhang told participants in today's national pharmaceutical
conference that enterprises on the list will be required to
allocate 3-5 percent of their annual sales for the research and
development of new drugs and technology.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 pharmaceutical companies, manufacturers of traditional
Chinese medicines, and enterprises engaged in the production of
medical instruments and devices will also be granted preferential
treatment, as well as some large enterprise groups, according to
Zheng.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 output value for China's pharmaceutical industry is
expected to reach 140 billion yuan (17 billion US dollars), up
12.5 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for the nationwide 1997 sales volume for
pharmaceutical products to hit 102 billion yuan (12 billion US
dollars), up 15 percent on 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
