<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China regions Join Hands in Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Five provinces and autonomous
regions in northwest China are vowing each other to enhance
cooperation in designing tourist routes and increasing tourism
transportation capacity in a bid to further tapping their rich
tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
Tourist officials attending a tourism cooperation meeting cited
close geographical proximity and special tourism features as the
condition for the further cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi, Gansu and Qinghai provinces, and Ningxia Hui and
Xinjiang Uygur autonomous regions boast unique tourism resources
of special characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Though local tourism was once hindered by relatively
less-developed economy, tourists from both at home and overseas
began to flock to the northwest in recently years to watch the
Terra-Cotta soldiers in Shaanxi, the Dunhuang Grottos in Gansu,
the grand monasteries and the grassland landscape in Qinghai, the
picturesque rivers and deserts in Ningxia, and the unique folklore
of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
As new opportunities for the development of local tourism have
been increasing, the five regions have been holding a meeting to
discuss tourism cooperation every year since the mid 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the recent meeting called for the further
increase in the number of air flights linking Xi'an, the venue of
the Terra-cotta Soldiers, with Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they hold that it necessary to open an air route
connecting Urumqi, the autonomous regional capital of Xinjiang,
with Dunhuang, and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The representative also proposed to work in cooperation to do
promotions at markets in north America, the Middle East, and
central Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Maintain Quick Pace In 1998: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China's leading economists and
sociologists forecast that in 1998 the country will continue to
develop with good economic results and stable social order.
</P>
<P>
According to an annual report issued by the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, the country will see a relatively high economic
growth rate the same as that in 1997, and there will be no sharp
pricehikes.
</P>
<P>
The report was written by a group of leading experts of the
prestigious institute, a think tank for the central government,
based on investigations, analysis and mathematical statistics.
</P>
<P>
The report says that living standards of both urban and rural
residents will be further improved, and the agricultural sector
will have a promising turnover.
</P>
<P>
It forecasts that a series of reform measures will be taken to
turn state-run enterprises into profit-making ones, adding that
publicly-owned firms will continue to dominate the economy, but
the number of private ones will increase.
</P>
<P>
It says that the year will be featured with a rapid growth of
the service industry.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment will become perhaps the biggest headache in 1998,
the report points out, saying that 11 million people will join in
the job-seeking army. Experts suggest that the government place
great emphasis on employment issue when drawing up macro-control
policies.
</P>
<P>
The report also calls for reforms in old-age insurance, medical
care and housing.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the report says, the term of the Eighth National
People's Congress will expire and new government leaders will be
elected. The report says that the government should adopt more
measures to improve its efficiency and govern the country in
accordance with law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
