<HEADLINE> Ford President Estimates World Auto Overproduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The president of the U.S. Ford
automaker Alex Trotman said Tuesday that the world automobile market
is suffering from a 40 percent overproduction.
</P>
<P>
"There is a 40 percent overcapacity in the world. There is above
all too much capacity in Europe, where the margin of manoeuvre in
automobile sale is becoming weaker and weaker," said Trotman in an
interview with the French economic daily La Tribune.
</P>
<P>
He said that there also exists the problem of automobile
overproduction in the United States, but the types of light trucks,
which are vehicles capable of running in all fields, are selling
well and are expected to take up 50 percent of the U.S. auto market
this year.
</P>
<P>
"The customers love the habitability of these vehicles, the high
position of driving, and the security procured by the four running
wheels," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Ford reduced 3 billion U.S. dollars of
costs in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
