<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso plunged
further to a new record low of 45.209 pesos against the U.S.
dollar in Tuesday's trading on the Philippine Dealing System
(PDS).
</P>
<P>
The peso averaged 44.810 to the greenback at mid-afternoon on
the PDS, the country's electronic currency exchange, down 3.072
pesos from Monday's reference rate of 41.738 pesos.
</P>
<P>
The peso slid from the opening, trading in a range of 44.35 to
45.209 pesos to the greenback before the market closed, on a thin
turnover of 9.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
No deals were made during the first 30 minutes of trading as
banks refused to buy the peso until financial officials relaxed
volatility limits and allowed the peso to plunge to the record
low.
</P>
<P>
The volatility bands were designed to prevent sharp currency
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
The peso has depreciated by 71 percent since the currency
crisis hit Southeast Asian nations in early July.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to us that what is driving the currency situation is
the overall (Southeast Asian) situation," Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he expected the Asian currency crisis to
likely stabilize by the end of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Confident of Steady Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said
Tuesday that the financial woes facing the Philippines currently
are temporary and the country's economic recovery will be steady
after the currency crisis settles down.
</P>
<P>
"There is widely-shared confidence -- here and abroad -- that
our financial woes are temporary, manageable and fully
surmountable," Ramos said in his sixth Report to the Nation.
</P>
<P>
When the turmoil settles down, Ramos said, the country's
"record of good housekeeping and strong economic fundamentals
should serve us well and our recovery will be steady and sure."
</P>
<P>
Despite the continuing depreciation of the country's currency,
the peso, Ramos assured the nation that the current economic
uncertainty constitutes neither a reversal of the gains the
country has made over the past five years nor a failure of the
country's growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso, which fell to 45.2 to the U.S. dollar
today, has so far depreciated more than 70 percent against the
greenback since its floatation in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, however, said the country is "a victim -- not an author
-- of the storm now engulfing Asia."
</P>
<P>
"Although some enterprises have had to retrench and some
projects had to be abandoned, our financial system remains sound
and stable," he said, adding that no financial institution has so
far been closed down in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos, one major cause leading to the country's
currency crisis is "the nervous flight of investor confidence from
the region" despite the country's "good housekeeping and sound
fundamentals."
</P>
<P>
Another explanation, Ramos said, is that in the face of
competitive devaluation in the region, the peso cannot afford to
stand still.
</P>
<P>
But he said the country's economic performance in 1997 showed
that the Philippines has avoided the overheating that has built up
in other parts of East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Asian financial turmoil, the Philippines' gross
national product (GNP) grew by 6 percent in real terms for the
first three quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also cited the robust growth of the country's exports,
surging investments and brisk tourism industry during the first
three quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the country's merchandise exports grew by 23
percent, helping reduce the trade deficit by 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and domestic investments in the country more than
quadrupled during the period to 613 billion pesos (15 billion
dollars) from 144 million pesos (3.6 billion dollars) recorded in
the same period of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
