<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Reserves Increase in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The South African Reserve
Bank's gold and foreign exchange reserves jumped by two billion
Rand (408 million U.S. dollars) in December, pushing the total
reserves to 28.5 billion Rand (5.82 billion dollars) by yearend,
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reserves stood at only 10.3 billion Rand (2.1 billion
dollars) in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase in reserves, which surprised economists, showed
the positive attitude of foreign investors, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The increase in December followed two months of falling
reserves as foreign investors lost appetite for risk in emerging
markets.
</P>
<P>
"The performance suggests that capital flows are once again
going in South Africa's favor," the Business Day newspaper quoted
Bertus van Zyl, a high-ranking Reserve Bank official, as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the increase in reserves did not prevent the plunge
of the Rand to a new low against the dollar at 4.9125 before
recovering slightly to 4.9095 at the end of Monday.
</P>
<P>
Van Zyl said the plunge was inevitable since the dollar was
strong on international markets.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be silly to expect the Rand to remain
unscathed while the dollar powered ahead on international
markets.
</P>
<P>
He said the Rand ended last year slightly stronger in nominal
terms compared with the start of the year. It ended the year 12
percent stronger than the Deutsch mark, 8.5 percent against the
Japanese yen, 1.8 percent weaker against the British pound and
3.7 percent against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Economists' forecasts for the end of 1998 range from 5.15 to
5.25 Rand to one dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
