<HEADLINE> Sampras and Hingis named world champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras of the United
Staytes and Martina Hingis of Switzerland have been made the
International Tennis Federation's 1997 world champions.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who increased his Grand Slam haul to 10 with victories
at the Australian Open and Wimbledon in 1997, is men's world
champion for the fifth successive year.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Hingis, who last year became the youngest
winner of a Grand Slam tournament when she won the Australian Open
when still only 16, is women's champion for the first time. The
Swiss teenager reached all four Grand Slam finals, losing only to
Croatia's Iva Majoli at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
The men's doubles champions are Australian pair Todd Woodbridge
and Mark Woodforde for a second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
Lindsay Davenport of the United States and Jana Novotna of the
Czech Republic are the women's doubles champions after showing an
impressive 33-6 record over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Cara Black of Zimbabwe was the world junior girls champion while
Arnaud di Pasquale of France was the junior boys champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
