<HEADLINE> South China City Bans Automobiles with Diesel Engines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital of south
China's Hainan Province, has banned automobiles with diesel engines
on road since the beginning of last December.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 automobiles driven by diesel engines, mainly
mini-buses, used to run in the 62-sq.km. urban area, bringing
heavy air pollution to the city, according to China Environmental
News.
</P>
<P>
"Some 150 old and shabby vehicles have been forced to be
scrapped, of which more than 80 percent are driven by diesel
engines," said an official with the city government.
</P>
<P>
The official said that over 3,000 automobiles have been
checked and maintained in accordance with the requirements of the
city's environmental department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city has bought 100 new buses and put into
operation a number of environment-friendly buses using liquefied
petroleum gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
