<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Near 11-Year Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar plummeted
to 11-year lows Tuesday, hit hard by a surging U.S. dollar, a soft
gold price and continuing concerns about the Asian currency
crisis.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since October 30, 1986, the local unit
closed below 64 U.S. cents, finishing the session at 63.47.
</P>
<P>
That was more than 1 U.S. cent lower than Monday's close of
64.82 U.S. cents and not far off the currency's low for the day of
63.33.
</P>
<P>
After being sold heavily offshore in response to a stronger
U.S. dollar against the Japanese yen and a slump in the price of
gold, the Australian dollar continued to falter in local trading.
</P>
<P>
Its troubles began following a rise in the greenback against
the Japanese yen, led by safe-haven buying which was caused by the
uncertainty in Asia and flows into bullish U.S. Treasury markets.
</P>
<P>
The slide was then exacerbated by a sharp drop in the price of
gold which recorded an 18-year low of 281 U.S. dollars an ounce
offshore.
</P>
<P>
"The latest wave of selling has been on the back of the opening
markets in Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand where those currencies
were sold aggressively at the start," Rothschild Australia manager
Paul Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah led Southeast Asian currencies down to
new record lows for the third straight trading session of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian ringgit, the Thai baht, the Philippine peso and
the Singapore dollar all followed suit.
</P>
<P>
"The market has just become totally obsessed with the fact that
the Asian situation is going to get a lot worse," Macquarie Bank
associate director Brent Aggar said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also ended at 84.83 against the Japanese
yen, from 85.73 on Monday and at 1.1628 Deutsche marks, from
1.1688. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
