<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill on Full Foreign Ownership in Kuwait Finalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors will be
able to set up independent ventures in Kuwait soon as a new bill
allowing full foreign ownership has been finalized, according to
official sources today.
</P>
<P>
A committee formed to study the draft law of foreign
investments completed its final reading of the bill last Saturday
and will relegate it to the cabinet for endorsement, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
The draft is part of a wider government strategy that is in
connection with the nation's privatization program to expand
private sector growth and an economic reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The bill allows for the first time in Kuwait any non-Kuwaiti
to hold 100 percent of a company through a license granted by the
Ministry of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are currently allowed to own only up to 49
percent shares in companies in Kuwait and levied by high local
corporate taxes.
</P>
<P>
These have been considered two of the main stumbling blocks to
attracting foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The bill allows foreign investors to recruit foreign manpower
if local workers are not available.
</P>
<P>
It also speaks of possible allocation of "necessary land and
real estate for the purposes of the investments" as well as
partial or complete exemption from customs duties for machines,
equipment and materials required by the investor.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, a foreign investor will be entitled to
transferring his profits and capital abroad and to another foreign
investors or national investors, provided the investments are
"environmentally sound."
</P>
<P>
Various authorities in the country hailed the draft law as a
positive first step as they think foreign investments would
introduce Kuwaiti to new technologies and create opportunities for
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
But they expressed fear that Kuwaitis would be dislodged from
their jobs as a result of the implementation of the new bill which
encourages the privatization process in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
