<HEADLINE> Divorce up 13 percent in Ho Chi Minh City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Divorce rate in Ho Chi Minh city,
the largest city of Vietnam, increased 13 percent in 1997 over
1996, the "Vietnam News" reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Out of 4,415 couples applying for divorce, 2,865 couples
successfully obtained divorces through the courts, the
English-language Daily quoted statistics from the Ho Chi Minh city
People's court as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Judicial authorities presiding over divorce cases in Ho Chi
Minh city blame the increasing rate of divorce on disappearing
of traditional family values.
</P>
<P>
Some judges believe that Vietnam must work hard to restore
family traditions and educate the young people on love, marriage
and family.
</P>
<P>
Impatience and a lack of respect for family values can both
impede conciliation, according to district judges.
</P>
<P>
Once divorce, the "Vietnam News" said, many fathers do not
perform their obligations to bring up their children.
</P>
<P>
Divorced fathers who refuse to financially support their
children may be inadvertently forced to try and earn their
own money on city streets, the daily added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
