<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Cyprus Peace Process Keeps Moving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 witnessed some
movements toward a settlement to the protracted Cyprus problem,
but there was no breakthrough despite rounds of direct talks
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
Under a proposal by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Cyprus
President, Greek Cypriot leader Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash met for the first time in four
years, in Troutbeck, near New York, in July to discuss ways of
solving the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In August, the second round of direct negotiations between
Clerides and Denktash, chaired by the U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor for Cyprus issue Diego Cordovez, was held in
Glion-sur-Montreaux, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately the five-day talks ended in failure as the
Turkish Cypriot side, which enjoys overall support of Turkey,
insisted on the suspension first by the European Union (EU) of its
planned accession negotiations with Cypriot government which is
protected by Greece, a staunch enemy of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Denktash charged the EU for throwing a "bombshell" into the
peace process by deciding to open accession talks with Cyprus
government next year.
</P>
<P>
In spite of failure of two rounds of direct negotiations, the
two leaders had two meetings in Nicosia, sponsored by the
U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel, to discuss
the humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
They reached an agreement on solving the long-standing issue
of missing persons during wars of the two communities on the
island, which constitutes an important aspect of the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two sides would exchange information
regarding the location of graves and prepare the necessary
arrangement leading to the return of the remains of the missing
persons.
</P>
<P>
This east Mediterranean island has been divided into the Greek
Cypriot-dominated south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks were listed as
missing persons after Turkish military intervention in 1974, while
the Turkish Cypriot side claims there are around 500 Turkish
Cypriots missing since the intercommunal clashes that broke out
in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash also agreed on exchange of visits for
pilgrimage by Greek and Turkish Cypriots, who have been
prohibited to cross the 180-kilometer-long U.N.-controlled buffer
zone since 1974.
</P>
<P>
Through these talks, it appears that at present the major
obstacle to the island's peace process is the issue of Cyprus' EU
accession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
