<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Cyprus Peace Process Keeps Moving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 18 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Through these talks, it appears that at present the major
obstacle to the island's peace process is the issue of Cyprus' EU
accession.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus submitted its application to the EU for full membership
in 1990 and believed that the accession cause could serve as a
catalyst for the resolution of the Cyprus problem, taking the EU
as its possible supporter vis-a-vis Turkey which has maintained
more than 30,000 troops in the Turkish-Cypriots controlled north.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided in March 1995 that the accession talks
with Cyprus would start six months after the end of the EU
Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU's decision was rejected by Turkey and the
Turkish Cypriot side, who maintained that Cyprus can not join the
EU before a Cyprus settlement and before Turkey becomes an EU
member.
</P>
<P>
Following an European Commission's reaffirmation on July 15
that the accession talks with Cyprus will begin in Spring
1998, Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot regime announced on July
20 a series of steps toward partial integration of the Turkish
occupied northern Cyprus with Turkey, a move apparently designed
to check the accession process.
</P>
<P>
But the EU did not give in to the Turkish integration threat
and decided in its Luxembourg summit in December to start
accession talks with Cyprus and five other central and eastern
European countries in Spring 1998.
</P>
<P>
The EU's move once again triggered furious reactions from
Denktash, who threatened to slammed the door on any further
inter-communal talks in the wake of the EU decision.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying that "the inter-communal talks have
died and under these conditions and a federation is not on the
agenda."
</P>
<P>
Denktash's statement has blocked the implementation of an
agreement reached between the two sides during visits to the
island by U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard Holbrooke and U.N.
envoy Diego Cordovez in November that direct negotiations between
the two leaders will resume next March, after the February
presidential elections in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, in response to the Turkish Cypriot reaction at the EU's
decision, had urged the two Cypriot sides to keep cool and adhere
to the primary objective of solving the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Clerides seems to be optimistic on a solution
to the Cyprus problem, saying that prospects for a Cyprus
settlement in 1998 will be good.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the U.N. and the U.S. are expected to intensify their
efforts to bring the two communities' leaders back to the
negotiating table despite Denktash's refusal to further
inter-communal talks in retaliation to the EU's decision.
</P>
<P>
But observers here noted that thorny issues concerning Cyprus
problem in the peace formulas, such as sovereignty, rotating
presidency, territorial adjustment and security for two
communities, have remained unsolved. Therefore, prospects of a
comprehensive settlement in Cyprus remain vague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Liberalizes Shipping Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's parliament, the People's
Assembly, has approved a law allowing local and foreign private
firms to compete with state-owned shipping companies, the Egyptian
Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The law, passed on Monday, allows the private sector to operate
maritime transport lines and provide maintenance, supply and
repairing services formerly monopolized by the state companies.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the country's drive to liberalize its economy and
increase foreign and private investment, according to Egyptian
Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
"What we look for is enhancing public interest and spurring the
Egyptian economy to widen the prospects of development," he told
the People's Assembly on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The law came in response to a demand by a host of economic
institutions that relevant curbs be lifted, Soliman Metwalli
Soliman, minister of transport and communications, explained to
the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
With the passage of the legislation, said Metwalli, the area
will be open to joint work and competition between public
enterprises and the private sector in an effort to provide better
services at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the handling capacity of Egypt's
ports reached 54 million tons last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
