<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls on UN to End Massacres in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran has called on the United
Nations to take immediate and constructive measures to put an end
to the massacres in Algeria, the local daily Iran News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent on Monday to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi expressed regret
for the "brutal and inhumane massacre of innocent Algerian women
and children and men."
</P>
<P>
He urged Annan to use all his power to bring the human tragedy
to a speedy end through contacts and consultations with all the
concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who country is now the chairman of the Organization
of the Islamic Conference, also deplored the silence of the
international community over the carnage.
</P>
<P>
"What causes further concern and anxiety is the suspicious
indifference and silence of the international community and
especially the Western countries." he said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Algerians were slain last week by unidentified
militants.
</P>
<P>
About 80,000 people have been killed in the Islamic insurgency
since 1992 when the military-backed Algerian government canceled a
parliamentary election in which the Islamic Salvation Front was
poised to win.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that "such barbaric massacres run counter to
Islamic humanitarian principles, values, norms and practices, and
constitute a dangerous and painful conspiracy which distorts the
image of Islam and Muslims across the world".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
