<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher on Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Banks led the Australian share
market higher again Tuesday because of the strong bond market,
with the all ordinaries index regaining lost territory since
October 22, the day before the market went on a four-trading-day
slide.
</P>
<P>
Brokers also said that there was off-shore buying in industrial
stocks and futures, with United States investors believed to be
the major buyers.
</P>
<P>
"It was a market continuation or reaction to a very strong bond
market, and it was valuation-driven buying because industrials
relative to bonds looked quite cheap," boutique funds manager and
investment house AUSBIL Partners equities director Paul Xiradis
said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed up 41 points at 2685.3. The
stock market, however, was still well below its peak of 2779.2
reached on September 22.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the all ordinaries index surpassed the October 22
closing level of 2682.9.
</P>
<P>
The bank sector gained 150.4 points, or 2.70 percent, to 5718.9
points, with National Australia Bank leading the market overall.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia also closed at a record high, up
35 cents, while Westpac Banking Corp was up 24 and ANZ Banking
Group was up 19.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index gained 92.5 points at 4616.4, but the
all resources index was down 3.2 points at 1142.9.
</P>
<P>
Falls in commodity prices and the potential impact of the Asian
meltdown on commodity exports has hit resource stocks hard.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slumped 27.2 points to 1002.3, wiping out the
gains in the sector made before the New Year. Gold bullion also
hit a fresh 18-year low on Tuesday as investors appeared to agree
with the economic textbooks that the precious metal was no longer
needed as a hedge against inflation.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 317.0 million shares with a value of
895.46 million Australian dollars (582 million U.S. dollars), and
rises of 595 outnumbered falls of 539.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
