<HEADLINE> US to Spearhead New Initiative on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
is set to spearhead a new initiative in the Middle East peace
process, the visiting U.S. congressman Nick Rahall has said.
</P>
<P>
Rahall, who is heading a 18-member delegation of
U.S. congressmen on a three-day visit to Lebanon, made the remarks
in an exclusive interview published today by the local English
paper the Daily Star.
</P>
<P>
He said the Clinton administration was in the process of
reversing its traditional bias in favor of Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said to the paper that after the conversation he had with
Clinton during a round of golf they played, he "understood from the
president that he is going to get more personally involved in the
peace process in the remaining three years of his term. I think
that he wants to make the Middle East peace agreement a legacy of
his administration."
</P>
<P>
The West Virginia democrat added that Clinton had expressed
his frustration at being unable to rally support among Arab
nations against Iraqi president Saddam Hussein, but he fully
understands that Arab nations would not support the U.S. until
they believe that the U.S. policy is no longer backing Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rahall and some of his delegation members are of Lebanese
descent. They came to Beirut on Sunday night and had held talks
with the country's President Elias Hrawi and Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri and House Speaker Nabih Berry on bilateral relations and
regional issues, especially south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
