<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Emerging as Major Employer in Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Non-government businesses in
China's Guangdong Province, mainly in the private sector, have
become a major source of employment recently.
</P>
<P>
The province now has more than 1.53 million privately-run
household businesses and larger companies, with 11.68 billion yuan
in registered capital. They employ nearly four million people,
providing a great deal of relief to the local economy, according
to a labor service official.
</P>
<P>
The demand for laborers has been dropping four percent annually
in recent years as reforms continue, and as the state-owned and
collective sectors contribute less to the national economy,
leaving 760,000 workers jobless in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the non-government economy in electronics,
clothing, and electrical appliances is doing well and added
120,000 jobs in the first three quarters of last year, accounting
for nearly half the province's total.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Dongguan, there are approximately one million
people working in foreign-funded enterprises, while only 120,000
work in the state sector.
</P>
<P>
The province estimates that there will be 450,000 redundant
workers annually during the 1996-2000 period, putting great
pressure on the economy. However, the growing non-government
sector, especially private businesses, will certainly have a role
to play in solving this problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
