<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hope Schools For Sui Nationality In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 8,000 Sui Nationality
children in southwest China's Guizhou Province have moved to new
classrooms in 21 Hope schools that were completed recently.
</P>
<P>
The schools were built with the help of donations from
businesses in the city of Shenzhen, one of China's special
economic zones in Guangdong Province, south China. They are
located in Guizhou's Sandu Sui Nationality Autonomous County,
where many young people had to drop out because of poor economic
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, a group of 400,000 people in Shenzhen donated 13.3
million yuan to the Hope Project fund.
</P>
<P>
In one year, Sandu County used 10.3 million yuan to build the
21 schools, which added 23,800 sq.m. of schoolrooms.
</P>
<P>
The county also used 3 million yuan to help 3,000 youngsters
who had dropped out return to school.
</P>
<P>
Li Wenzhi, the county's Party secretary, says that the aid from
Shenzhen has helped the Sui people escape their illiterate state.
</P>
<P>
The drop-out rate in the county fell from 1995's 12 percent to
2 percent in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
