<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti PM Rules Out Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Prime Minister
Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah has denied reports about a
cabinet reshuffle or a plan to dissolve the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
According to local media today, the crown prince also turned
down the resignation of Finance Minister Nasser Abdullah Al-Rudhan.
</P>
<P>
There will be "no dissolution of the Assembly, no cabinet
resignation and no reshuffle," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Local reports had said that a cabinet reshuffle or dissolution
of the parliament may take place because of Al-Rudhan, who
submitted his resignation to the prime minister on November 15.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rudhan said he thought of quitting the post last July after
facing interpellations by three parliament members over alleged
financial mismanagement, irregularities in handling public funds
and negligence leading to sizable losses by Kuwait Airways
Corporation and the Public Institution for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, religious groups and liberals in the 50-seat
parliament have been preparing a second grilling at the finance
minister, who has answered 168 questions in the parliament over the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
This made him angrily assert that it is difficult to work in
such an environment.
</P>
<P>
The situation, which has strained the relations between the
parliament and the cabinet, is believed to be on the brink of a
political crisis that may lead to a cabinet reshuffle or the
dissolution of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
But Sheikh Saad stressed that government decisions cannot be
based on reactions or emotions, saying that there is no discussion
of government reshuffle or dissolving the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Al-Rudhan is a dedicated colleague who has exerted a huge
effort. I want him to continue because I am sure he is still
capable of performing," said the prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FINA Sticks with Four-year Ban for Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, Australia, January 6 (Xinhua) -- World swimming's
governing body FINA on Tuesday has decided to retain four-year
penalties for first doping offenders.
</P>
<P>
At its Congress on the eve of the world swimming championships,
FINA president Mustapha Lafaoui called a halt to a debate on
whether to move to two-year bans.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Australia, Britain, Barbados and Denmark spoke
for retaining four-year bans.
</P>
<P>
The IOC wants all sports to meet standard two-year bans for
first offenders because of difficulty in forcing four-year
suspensions in the face of international court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
The International Amateur Athletic Federation has changed their
bans to two years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, FINA leaders pushed for a return to a two-year ban,
citing costly litigation and legal problems with the four-year
sanction.
</P>
<P>
But the shorter penalty was rejected when Congress delegates
from the United States, Australia and Britain spoke strongly
against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
