MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) Tuesday admitted to have been recipient of foreign
support, including those coming from Western countries, especially
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice-chairman for military affairs,
confirmed foreign sources have substantially contributed to their
cause for the past years, the Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we do receive foreign funding, some of which come from
American-Arab brothers," Murad was quoted by the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the state-of-the-art communications and computer
facilities found at Camp Abubakar, MILF largest camp in Central
Mindanao, were acquired through the help of generous American-Arab
donors, Murad said.
</P>
<P>
Camp Abubakar boasts of modern computer stations, facsimile
machines and internet connections as well as local and
international satellite phone facilities.
</P>
<P>
The MILF also declared to have acquired sophisticated weapons,
like a battery of mobile surface-to-air-missiles, which require
radar and computer facilities.
</P>
<P>
But the military dismissed this as "pure fantasy." However,
Romeo Padiernos, Southern Command chief of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines, admitted that if the reports are true, the army would
be placed in a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group also claimed to have been manufacturing its own
anti-tank weapons inside Camp Abubakar, including rocket propelled
grenades, a shoulder-fired weapon effective in short distance
encounters.
</P>
<P>
Lately, the MILF also boasted of some 180,000 fully-armed
fighters in Mindanao. The military, however, estimated the group's
strength of more than 8,000 men only, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is presently the biggest Muslim separatist
organization in the country, which broke away from the Muslim
National Liberation Front, a former Muslim group which forged
peace accord with the government in September 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
