<HEADLINE> Ansett Airline to Suspend Australia-ROK Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia's second largest
airline Ansett announced Tuesday it would suspend its bi-weekly
flights between Australia and the Republic of Korea from February
6.
</P>
<P>
Ansett International General Manager Craig Wallace said the
economic crisis in Seoul meant that its Korean services,
inaugurated in 1996, were no longer commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
He said a sharp decline in the value of the Korean won and
restrictions on the promotion of outbound tourism from Korea had
resulted in a fall in passenger numbers.
</P>
<P>
The move follows the decision made by Qantas, Australia's
largest airline, last week to suspend its four-times-a-week
service to ROK from February 1.
</P>
<P>
Qantas Airways Ltd. said it had in the past month experienced a
drop in nearly 65 percent in demand for seats on the route,
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian tourism industry said it was concerned about the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
Australian Tourist Commission Managing Director John Morse said
the effects of the Korean economic crisis on Australia's tourism
industry were short to mid term and the long term future was
positive.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about the implications of this morning's
announcement by Ansett to suspend services to South Korea," Morse
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"However, we acknowledge the airlines need to make tough
commercial decisions which may not always be in the best interests
of Australia's tourism industry."
</P>
<P>
Until recent months Korea was Australia's fastest growing
tourism market which, Morse said, accounted for six percent of the
total visitor arrivals to Australia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tourism Council Australia General Manager Scott
Morrison said strong industry growth could be maintained through
new markets, such as India and China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
