<HEADLINE> Former Chinese Capital Attracts More Tourists in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, the capital of China's
Jiangsu Province and the capital of several ancient Chinese
dynasties, had some successes in its fledgling tourist industry in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The total number of tourists in the city reached 10 million for
the first time, with a record 10 billion yuan in business,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The city has made an effort to develop tourism and spent 500
million yuan on a number of new tourism sites and infrastructure,
last year. Local tourism authorities promoted tourism around the
country by organizing tours in other cities.
</P>
<P>
The city has also increased its number of accommodations and
now has 105 hotels that can house foreign tourists. It also has 75
travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
It had 295,000 overseas visitors in 1997, up 20.4
percent from the previous year, and 9.84 million Chinese visitors,
an increase of 25.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tourism earnings accounted for 13.21 percent of the city's GDP
last year, hitting an all-time high. 
</P>
