begin its business partnership with its sister city Tianjin by
opening an office in the Chinese port city, Lord Mayor Ivan
Deveson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Melbourne Office is a first for Australian local
government and will promote two way business and investment
between Melbourne and Tianjin - the third largest city in China,"
Deveson said.
</P>
<P>
Melbourne is the second largest industrial and commercial city
in Australia following Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The Melbourne Office is intended to operate as a base in
Tianjin for Australian and Chinese business and government
networks, he was quoted by the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
But the news agency did not say when it would open.
</P>
<P>
A Melbourne City Council spokesman said the idea is to provide
"a foot in the door" for companies wishing to establish businesses
overseas.
</P>
<P>
"We believe Tianjin has been, and will continue to be a hotspot
for foreign investment in China," said Bill O'Sheam, president of
the Australia China Business Council (Victorian state).
</P>
<P>
"It has a switched-on government which is able to fast-track
approvals and one of the best deep-water ports in China," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Deveson said the opening of Melbourne's office would facilitate
other exchanges between the two cities, such as artistic
scholarships and discussions on city management. 
