<HEADLINE> Corruption Behind Pretoria Prison Escape: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Corrupt prison officials
probably helped six dangerous awaiting-trial prisoners escape
from South Africa's Pretoria Local Prison on December 5, The Star
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The task team assigned to investigate the jail break had
passed its conclusions, along with specific recommendations to
President Nelson Mandela and the office of Justice Minister
Dullah Omar, head of the team, Stefan Grobler, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have strong evidence of corruption, and are moving on to
the next step which is to recapture the six men," Grobler said.
</P>
<P>
The six men, all still at large, were involved in
multi-million-dollar robberies and crime syndicates.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to prove the corruption and in order to do this we
need to re-arrest the six fugitives and, through questioning, get
them to reveal their inside contacts -- people either in
correctional services or the police," Grobler said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that these men will be recaptured,
but didn't say how and when.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the task team will not be made public until
they had been handled by relevant ministries, Grobler said.
</P>
<P>
Jail breaks are frequent in South Africa. A total of 678
prisoners escaped in November and December alone.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Party called for an independent
investigation into the problems within the Department of
Correctional Services while the United Democratic Movement also
urged the government to appoint an independent commission to
investigate deficiencies in the police and correctional services.
</P>
</TEXT>
