<HEADLINE> Manila to Launch Reforms to Stabilize Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said Tuesday that the government will launch "a second generation
of reforms" to stabilize the economy and increase economic
competitiveness in the global market.
</P>
<P>
In his 1997 year-end report, Ramos said the current financial
crisis provides an opportunity for the Philippines to strengthen
the economy by "launching a second generation of reforms crucial
to our economic stability and competitiveness in the world
economy."
</P>
<P>
Addressing hundreds of government officials and foreign
diplomats, Ramos said it is just "a matter of time, of good
management, and of resolute leadership" for the country to recover
from the spreading currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
On top of the six key reform measures is the completion of the
policy environment to make the economy more competitive in the
world and more resilient against shocks and crises, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Under this measure, the country will enact, among other vital
bills, fisheries and land use codes, a new oil deregulation law
and an anti-corruption bill.
</P>
<P>
The government will also develop and strengthen its capital
markets and national savings rate, foster a competitive and stable
exchange rate, and liberalize retail trade.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also promised to improve the government's capacity and
efficiency across the board by streamlining the bureaucracy,
fighting graft and corruption and continuously innovating
government systems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos stressed, the government will continue to
improve education and training in the country and upgrade its law
and order systems.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Ramos also called on the Filipinos to rekindle
the spirit characterized by resilience, nationalism, and sense of
unity, in face of the prolonged financial storm.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was hit by the region-wide currency crisis in
July when the Central Bank was forced to float the peso after the
devaluation of the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
The peso, which sank sharply to 45.14 pesos to the U.S. dollar
Tuesday, has lost more than 70 percent in its value since its
floatation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
