<HEADLINE> Nagano Gets First Big Snowfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The first major snowfall of the
winter fell on the land of Hakuba on Tuesday, just one month
before the start of the Nagano Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
It began snowing early on Tuesday, the same day a torch relay
carrying the Olympic flame got under way.
</P>
<P>
By mid-afternoon about 20 centimeters (eight inches) had
fallen in Hakuba, where the cross country and many of the Alpine
skiing events will take place.
</P>
<P>
A lack of snow in the mountain resort, 50 km (30 miles) from
Nagano, had raised concerns about preparations for the February
7-22 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"It has already snowed 20 centimetres in Hakuba and I'm
expecting about 10 more (four inches) by midnight," Nagano
Organising Committee weather official Tamahiro Kimino said.
</P>
<P>
"But I'm not sure how many snowfall days there will be for the
rest of January," Kimino said.
</P>
<P>
The torch relay started on Tuesday in three different
locations in Japan on a 33-day journey. The three flames will be
carried by a total of 1,150 runners through all 47 of Japan's
prefectures.
</P>
<P>
The three flames will be reunited in Nagano on February 6,
one day before the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A warmer-than-normal winter so far has meant that any snow
which has fallen in Nagano city and on the lower sections of
nearby mountains has melted.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature in December in Nagano was 2.8
degrees Celsius (37 Fahreneit), compared to a normal average of
1.7 C (35 F), Kimino said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
