<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Speed up Rural Electrification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Electricity Supply
Authority (ZESA) has decided to spend 460 million Zimbabwe
Dollars (27 million U.S. dollars) this year to accelerate the
rural electrification program, The Herald daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ZESA has identified 46 rural centres countrywide which
will benefit from the program. The 46 centers lie along the lines
to service 28 schemes which have been approved by the government
under the authority's rural electricification master plan. Work
on some of the centres has already started while others are still
open for bids.
</P>
<P>
Five of the country's non-metropolitan provinces are expected
to benefit under the program with the remaining provinces having
to wait for the next phase of the program sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 80 projects covering 171 rural service centres
would have been electrified during the first phase of the
authority's master plan for the 21st century which begins in 1999
and ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Some 91 schemes covering 244 rural service centres are also
expected to have been electrified during the second phase of the
program from 2002 to 2007 at a cost of more than 460 million
Zimbabwe Dollarss (over 27 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
