<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Safe in Iranian Airliner's Emergency Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- All passengers and crew are sound
and safe after an Iranian airliner was forced to make an emergency
landing on a desert in central Iran Monday night, Iran's radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran-bound plane with 113 people - 104 passengers and
nine crew members - on board was forced to land in the desert due
to a unspecified technical failure.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the Iranian aviation authorities failed to
locate the landing place due to the darkness at night.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, the helicopters searching for the plane
found it in the desert east to the ancient city of Isfahan, about
400 kilometers south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
All the 104 passengers have been moved from the plane to a
hotel in the nearby town, the radio said, and the passengers would
be transferred to Tehran by another plane this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The plane, whose type was not mentioned, was flying from
Orumiye, in the westernmost part of the country to Tehran. But due
to the bad weather, it could not land at Tehran airport and was
directed to Isfahan.
</P>
<P>
Around 22:00 local times (18:30 GMT) Monday night, the plane
disappeared from the control radar. Soon after the incident,
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami ordered relief groups to be
rushed to the desert to search and rescue the people on board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
