<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Edition of "Encyclopedia of Human Rights" Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese version of "The
Encyclopedia of Human Rights", compiled by Edward Lawson, an
American political science professor, was recently published in
China, according to the publisher, the Sichuan People's Publishing
House.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Muzhi, president of the China Society for Human Rights
Studies, and Ibrahima Fall, director of the UN Center for Human
Rights and UN assistant secretary-general for human rights, wrote
prefaces to the Chinese version.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the publisher say that it took several years for
dozens of Chinese scholars to translate the four-million-word
encyclopedia, which has more than 800 entries.
</P>
<P>
The book is a collection of more than 200 important human
rights documents from the UN and other international
organizations, and a discussion of the human rights situation in
165 nations and regions. It contains information on major
inter-governmental and non-governmental human rights
organizations and a number of well-known human rights cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
