<HEADLINE> Improved Asset Evaluation Prevents Large Losses in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Last year, Shanghai municipal
authorities prevented 145 million US dollars worth of losses by
assessing the value of equipment imported by foreign investors,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jihao, Director of the Commodity Inspection Bureau's
Property Evaluation Agency, told Xinhua that some overseas
businessmen had tried to profit by overstating the value of
equipment they had imported for local projects.
</P>
<P>
Since the agency was set up in 1993, it has evaluated of
equipment brought in by foreign investors in over 1,500
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Some 530 items with a total declared value of 390 million US
dollars were appraised, and 50 percent of them were found to have
inflated claims that were worth nearly 50 million US
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
