<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Announces 20 Percent Reduction of Ports' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean government has
announced a 20 percent reduction of ports' tariff to increase the
competitive capacity of its two ports in the region.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea has two ports, namely Massawa and Assab along its long
coastline of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to a notice published on the latest issue of the
"Eritrea Profile", this is the third time that the Eritrean
government revised its ports tariff since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The new ports' tariff announced by the government includes:
</P>
<P>
-- a 20 percent tariff reduction for overall services;
</P>
<P>
-- a 50 percent discount on port dues and 10 percent reduction
of stevedoring and shore handling for transhipment cargoes;
</P>
<P>
-- 50 percent reduction on conservancy, berthing and bouyage,
and shore crane charges for Eritrean national vessels;
</P>
<P>
-- reduction of charges from 11.90 U.S. dollars to five
dollars for fire fighting truck attendance;
</P>
<P>
-- reduction of charges from 214.00 dollars to 50.00 dollars
for tug boat attendance;
</P>
<P>
-- charging only 60 percent of the conservancy, burthing, and
bouyage charges for vessels which visit the port for provisions,
bunkering or repair;
</P>
<P>
-- a 30 percent discount from the normal stevedoring rate for
roll on roll of cargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
