<HEADLINE> Share Prices Down Sharply on Singapore Market Midday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined sharply
on the Singapore market on Tuesday as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index plunged by 63.13 points to end the morning
session of trading at 1432.82 points, the lowest level in more
than five years.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said share prices plummeted by 4.2 percent, reflecting
investors' concerns over the falling Asian currencies, which took
a tumble on Monday, with the Indonesian rupiah, Thai baht,
Malaysian ringgit and Philippine peso dropping to new record lows.
</P>
<P>
The sell-off in the stock market "is basically
currency-driven," said a dealer with a foreign brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
However, other dealers here said the thin trading conditions
had exaggerated the losses in share prices as some panicky
investors dumped their positions.
</P>
<P>
The market volume stood at 56.64 million units, valued at
124.07 million Singapore dollars (about 72.13 million U.S.
dollars). There were 296 counters that declined while only 13
stocks registered increases and a total of 302 stocks remained
steady.  
</P>
</TEXT>
