<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine government has raised imports tariffs
by 3 percent since January 1, on the basis of an accord between
partner countries of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
The new tariffs apply to goods from all countries but Brazil,
Uruguay and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's exports of manufactured products stood
at 2.15 billion U.S. dollars in the first 11 months of 1997, an
increase of 13.56 percent over 1.89 billion dollars in the same
period in 1996, the Ministry of Foreign Commerce said Monday.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean exports were 16.8 billion dollars in 1997,
an increment of 4.7 percent over 1996's volume, said the Foreign
Ministry`s Exports Fostering Office head Hector Casanueva.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The government of Managua is to create some 150,000
jobs in 1998, the Labor Minister Wilfredo Navarro announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Navarro said that the private sector generated 80,000 new jobs
in 1997, and he expected the figure to double this year.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian footwear industry's output went
down by 6 percent in 1997 from 1996 due to lack of domestic
demand, Brazil's Association of Footwear Makers said.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Trade between Puerto Rico and Panama posted
69.4 million dollars in the fiscal year 1996-1997, a 55 percent
increase over the last fiscal period, said the Puerto Rico
Commercial Office to Panama Monday.
</P>
<P>
Puerto Rico's exports to Panama ammounted to 44.7 million
dollars, while sales from Panama to Pueto Rico reached 24.7
million dollars. 
</P>
