<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Seek Review of IMF Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda has moved ahead his planned meeting with
International Monetary Fund (IMF) officials to review the terms on
the IMF providing a 17.2 billion U.S. dollar bailout package.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin had planned to visit the United States in February for
talks with the IMF officials, but the trip has been moved to
January due to the urgency of the situation, the Bangkok Post
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the Thai currency baht broke through the major
psychological barrier of 50 baht to the U.S. dollar by hitting
51.1 baht, before rebounding to 49.8 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The plunge of the baht on the first trading day following the
new year holiday drove the baht further near the next major
psychological notch of 51.58, at which the baht will have lost 100
percent of its value against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
When the IMF bailout package was drawn out last August, the IMF
was somewhat too optimistic about Thailand's economy and based its
terms on 33 baht to the dollar. Before July 2 last year when the
baht was allowed to float, the exchange rate was 25.79 baht to the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
With the further fluctuation of the baht and the credit crunch,
it 1s now almost impossible for Thailand to meet the IMF condition
of maintaining a budget surplus equal to 1 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP), or about 69 billion baht (1.38 billion
dollars) in fiscal 1998, which ends on September 30, the Bangkok
Post Tuesday quotes Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai as saying on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that other issues which Tarrin will
discuss with IMF officials include Thailand's economic growth
targets for 1998 and domestic interest rate policies.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some Thai state agencies said the economy was
likely to register a negative growth in 1998, as compared to an
IMF request of between zero and one percent economic growth.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates have kept ailing investors from seeking
loans, which are essential for revitalizing businesses.
</P>
<P>
A downward revision in GDP targets could ease pressure on the
government to further slash the budget in order to generate a
surplus of one percent as agreed with the IMF before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
