<HEADLINE> Mexico's Foreign Secretary Goes to Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Foreign Secretary
Angel Gurria has been relieved of this post and reappointed
finance secretary by President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the portfolio change Monday, Gurria said he will
stick to the current economic policy and further advance the
sustained and stable development of Mexico's economy.
</P>
<P>
Gurria, 47, graduated from the National Autonomous University
of Mexico and gained a master's degree in public finances at Leeds
University in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He also worked as general manager of the state-run National
Bank of Foreign Commerce as well as of the National Credit Bank,
and was appointed foreign minister in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The former finance secretary, Guillermo Ortiz, has been
reappointed president of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo, in his announcement, praised Ortiz for his work in the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
This is the second personnel change in the cabinet at the
beginning of this year. Zedillo reappointed former agriculture
secretary, Francisco Labastida, as his interior secretary on
January 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
