<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Get Into Jaffna to Cripple Polls: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Tamil rebels have
sent additional guerrillas to the Jaffna peninsula to intensify
attacks and cripple the local government elections scheduled for
January 29, military sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Five people believed to be rebel infiltrators were killed by
troops on Saturday and Sunday in the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The military said that the rebels had made their way into the
Jaffna region to step up attacks on military installations as well
as to disrupt the northern local government elections, the first
in about ten years in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Chandrika Kumaratunga has expressed her
government's keenness to hold free and fair elections to the local
bodies in the north when she met a Tamil political party leader on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
She assured the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front
that she had issued strict instructions to the police and the
election staff to maintain impartiality and to leave no room for
any abuse or irregularity that could mar the polls.
</P>
<P>
A total of 571,484 voters are to cast their ballots at 422
polling stations to elect 234 representatives for municipal, urban
and village councils in Jaffna and Kilinochchi districts in the
north.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,171 candidates are to run the elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
