<HEADLINE> Brazil Exported 138 Million Tons Of Iron In 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Brazil exported last year 138
million tons of iron, which means a 30-million-ton rise against
1996.
</P>
<P>
Iron exports were worth three billion dollars, said Monday the
Vale Do Rio Doce company, the leading Brazilian exporter of
minerals.
</P>
<P>
This year, Brazil is expected to export more than 140 million
tons of the product.
</P>
<P>
The company announced that Brazilian iron exporters are meeting
Japanese and German clients next January 12 and 13 in order to
discuss export quotas of iron as well as international prices.
</P>
<P>
Japanese buyers want to keep iron prices at similar levels to
those in 1997 (17.7 dollars per ton). But Brazil argues that the
real price for an iron ton is 18.77 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian iron producer said that during 1996, 393 million
tons of iron were traded worldwide and that amount rose in 1997 to
425 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Brazil and Australia made up 65 percent of the total world
trade of iron last year.
</P>
<P>
Iron trade could reach 450 million tons worldwide by 2000, said
sources of Vale Do Rio Doce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
