<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Civil Aviation Gets Big Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China invested a record 11
billion yuan in 1997 in renovating and upgrading the country's
civil aviation, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The investment, pumped by the government into renovation and
infrastructure projects, was aimed primarily at enhancing the
Chinese airlines' operational safety and efficiency, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, about 800 million yuan (about 96.38
million US dollars) was channeled to build or upgrade airports and
their support facilities, and 300 million yuan was poured to key
technological renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
Among the 21 key construction projects, airports at Zhengzhou,
Guiyang, Nanjing, Fuzhou, Yinchuan, Hefei, Nanning, Hohhot and
Xuzhou across the country were completed and opened to traffic in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Before the year 2000, China plans to build and upgrade 41
airports, whose combined handling capacity will account for 95
percent of the country's total, to cater to soaring future demand,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The country's civil aviation business skyrocketed by an average
of 20.5 percent annually for 16 years, 3.6 times higher than the
figure of member countries of the International Aviation
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
