<HEADLINE> Mexico's New Interior Secretary Proposes Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's new Interior
Secretary, Francisco Labastida, said on Monday that his ministry
is about to submit a strategic plan to renew and foster a peace
dialogue in the state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said it is necessary that the government takes on
the role of encouraging conciliation and mutual understanding in
the troubled state.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chiapas issue cannot be settled with a
one-sided effort. All the people involved have to play their parts
in the process.
</P>
<P>
Labastida said he is holding talks with members of the
Pacification and Settlement Commission, which consists of deputies
of the National Congress and represents the government in the
suspended dialogue with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said he will meet leaders of several religious organizations
in Chiapas in order to outline a new plan to bring peace to the
region.
</P>
<P>
One of its main goals is to make sure nobody in the state owns
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
He added that when people own arms, violence emerges. He said
the government could not accept that some groups be disarmed while
others were not, referring to the rebel Zapatista National
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
The Zapatista guerrillas, who waged an uprising against the
government in January 1994, demanded special treatment from the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
Labastida, who assumed his post last Saturday, said the
conflicting regions in Chiapas are plagued by land and
religion-related fights, which have caused many people to
flee their towns to live under "inhuman conditions".
</P>
<P>
The rebels and Mexican press condemned the December 22 massacre
of 45 indigenous people in Chenalho, Chiapas, saying the attack
could have been prevented by the government from happening.
</P>
<P>
The Zapatistas blamed the government for its alleged funding of
paramilitary groups which were said to have perpetrated the
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The massacre prompted the resignation of the former interior
secretary Emilio Chuayffet, after he was strongly criticized for
the handling of the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
