<HEADLINE> Macedonian President Calls for Mediterranean Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Mediterranean countries should
unite and collaborate with each other on the basis of mutual
understanding to cope with the threats to peace in the region,
Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov said in Naples on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gligorov made the remark at a ceremony where he received the
Mediterranean peace award from the "Laboratorio Mediterraneo"
foundation.
</P>
<P>
He said peace in the Mediterranean continues to be at risk
because of historic rivalries and the growing gap between the rich
north and the poor south.
</P>
<P>
"Historic frustrations, instead of easing, have sharpened,
creating fertile ground for exclusivism, intolerance and
terrorism", Gligorov said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, historic rivalries in the region have created in
the Mediterranean basin the largest arsenal in the world, and no
solution has been figured out so far to the decades-long frictions.
</P>
<P>
Gligorov appealed to all nations bordering the Mediterranean to
create conditions for a stable peace through common action,
collaboration, solidarity and reciprocal understanding between all
peoples in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian president also attended a ceremony for the
signing of an agreement aimed at promoting cultural exchanges
between the Naples Institute for Oriental Studies and the
University of Skopije. 
</P>
</TEXT>
