<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks to Repatriate Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will take
measures to repatriate all foreign laborers within three years to
ease rising unemployment among Thais, according to Minister of
Labor and Social Welfare Trairong Suwannakhiri.
</P>
<P>
Trairong was quoted by Tuesday's local newspapers as saying
that the government aimed to repatriate from 300,000 to 500,000
foreign workers -- mainly from Myanmar, South Asia and Indochina
-- per year, as it wanted to alleviate unemployment faced by Thais
because of the economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry will set a time limit in each province
where employers are allowed to hire foreign workers. Employers
will be notified about the repatriation policy ahead of the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
After the deadline, any employer found violating the order will
face three years imprisonment or a 60,000 baht (1,200 US dollars)
fine.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that with the drastic action within three
years, all foreign workers will be repatriated," he said
</P>
<P>
Only 300,000 foreign workers have registered with the Ministry
of Labor and Social Welfare out of an estimated more than one
million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Trairong said his ministry will not renew work permits for
foreign workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
