<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wind to Bring Light to Poor Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A national project aimed at
bringing clean electricity generated by wind-driven turbine
systems to China's millions of poor rural people is set to begin
operating this year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Project Light, as it is named by officials of the State
Planning Commission (SPC), not only will benefit millions of rural
people living in poverty, but also will improve China's
pollution-prone power supply mix, 75 percent of which comes from
burning coal, the paper quoted an official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Li Hongxun, deputy director of the department of transportation
and energy, made the remarks Monday in Beijing while attending a
signing ceremony of the establishment of a Sino-foreign joint
venture, named the Sino-US Xiangtan Bergey Windpower Co. (XBWC),
the first of its kind in China, which is expected to provide the
project with quality wind turbines and wind-driven generators.
</P>
<P>
As part of Project Light, XBWC is expected to bring electricity
to China's poverty-stricken isolated islands, frontier guard posts
and communication hubs and thousands of remote villages as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
China has 72 million people living without electricity in
24,800 remote villages of 11 counties and 649 towns, the latest
survey by the SPC indicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
