<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asian Tourism Facing Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- After 1997 proved to be a
disastrous year for Southeast Asia's tourism, 1998 may bring some
luck to the industry, but only "hard luck."
</P>
<P>
Last year, Southeast Asia's tourism suffered a big setback when
a series of disasters hit the region, once touted as one of the
world's fastest growing and most dynamic.
</P>
<P>
First, there were the currency crises, which forced potential
tourists in Thailand, South Korea, Japan and rest of East Asia to
take belt-tightening measures, including cancellations of travel
to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Then came the environmental hazards posed by Indonesia's forest
fires, which destroyed tens of thousands of hectares of forests
and scattered health-threatening haze over the whole Southeast
Asian region. The haze drastically affected tourism in Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The depression in the region's tourism surprised many people,
especially government officials, who had mis-judged the extent of
the financial crisis and had not expected the haze problem.
</P>
<P>
When a Thai financial crisis spread to other Southeast Asian
nations last July, regional currencies became 10 to 30 percent
weaker against the U.S. dollar in weeks. Government leaders then
expected that the weaker currencies, though hurting regional
economies, would make their export products more competitive and
attract dollar-holding tourists.
</P>
<P>
However, currency devaluation failed to promote the growth of
the industry as weaker currencies and plummeting stock markets
have only kept tourists from the region at home. Over the past 10
years, Southeast Asians had become rich enough to travel within
their region, and made up half of the region's tourist traffic.
The financial crisis effectively reduced the number of tourist
arrivals in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in the summer, giant forest fires in Indonesia raised
a pall of smoke over vast parts of Southeast Asia. The ecological
disaster scared away would-be tourists from the west and rest of
the world in the later part of the year.
</P>
<P>
Now the haze is over, but the crisis is still lingering in the
region. Could the situation be improved in 1998?
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the better environment and the weaker currencies
would attract long-haul visitors, but moves by Asian governments
to discourage their people to trip abroad would pose a new
challenge to the region's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
American airlines and travel agents reported recently that
plummeting currencies in Korea, Malaysia, Thailand and the
Philippines will likely promote more Americans to take advantage
of the exchange rate and vacation in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The declining value of regional currencies means the dollar
buys more of the Southeast Asian goods, including hotel rooms,
food and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
In the last six month, currencies of Thailand, the Philippines,
Indonesia, and Malaysia declined by 30 to 60 percent while South
Korea's won has lost half of its value against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
People from other west nations are also expected to take the
advantages of the weaker currencies and travel in the region,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
However, less trips by Southeast Asians within the region will
affect the recovery of the tourism industry. Recently, governments
in the region are taking measures to discourage their people from
going abroad.
</P>
<P>
They are raising passport fees and other international travel
costs, and even openly urging people not to go abroad, as part of
efforts to protect their foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has reportedly doubled the cost of passports to 300
ringgit (78 dollars) or 600 ringgit, depending on the number of
pages requested. Thailand is considering raising international
airport taxes and discussing imposing an exit tax.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has suspended foreign trips by
government officials, including attendance in foreign conferences,
training, cultural and social and sports activities.
</P>
<P>
Facing both new opportunities and challenges, Southeast Asian
governments launched new campaigns to promote tourism. In
Thailand, the government has just kicked off an "Amazing Thailand"
campaign that hopes to attract 17 million tourists this year.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the government will hold an international
tourism conference "the Philippine Tourism Investment
Opportunities" at the end of this month in a bid to lure more
foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
Most of Southeast Asian governments are urging their people to
boost tourism by having domestic tours.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts will certainly help bring about an early
recovery of the industry, but the on-going financial crisis still
could dampen hopes of tourism boom this year, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
