<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales Seen to Drop in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Because of the current currency
crisis, automotive vehicle sales in the Philippines are expected
to drop by 23 percent to 109,000 units this year from 142,000
units in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Car sales will plunge by 30 percent to 53,000 units from 75,000
units, while commercial vehicle sales will drop by 15 percent to
57,000 units from 68,000 units, local press reports Tuesday quoted
industry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mario de Grano, secretary general of the Chamber of Automotive
Manufacturers of the Philippines, said the weak market demand will
be aggravated by the continuing fall of the peso and the increase
in the tariff rate on car parts kits.
</P>
<P>
"People are expected to start buying (cars) only after the
(May) elections," De Grano said, adding that the forecast may yet
be refined when the chamber members meet to consolidate the
figures.
</P>
<P>
As of November, total motor vehicle sales reached only 135,000
units. Passenger car sales for the first 11 months of 1997 was
placed at 70,805 units while commercial vehicle sales was recorded
at 64,195 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
