<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Economy Expects Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy's economy is continuing to
expand and the recovery is expected to be consolidated during the
next few months, the National Institute for Economic Trends (ISCO)
said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the treasury think-tank, the strengthening of the
national economy would not put pressure on prices and inflation
would remain under control.
</P>
<P>
Although the economy was not expected to grow more than in
recent months, ISCO noted that Italian business viewed the first
quarter of 1998 with "widespread optimism".
</P>
<P>
Companies forecast that "the economy will continue to recover
at a moderate rate, while pressure on prices is expected to fall",
ISCO said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, relatively few companies intended to raise their
prices in coming months, the institute added.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand was reported stable, while orders from abroad
were increasing slightly. Industrial production for the first
quarter was expected to remain at the high levels of 1997,
according to ISCO.
</P>
<P>
A further indication that the Italian economy was expanding
came from the national electricity board Enel, which reported on
Monday that demand for electric power had risen by 3.8 percent in
1997 compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Enel said the increase in demand recorded in every month since
April 1997 had initially been confined to industrial sectors
influenced by government incentives, such as auto production.
</P>
<P>
The recovery had then spread to all sectors of the economy
except construction, with companies producing finished goods
showing particular strength and hence demanding more electricity
to drive production, Enel said.
</P>
<P>
The results had exceeded all expectations and showed a marked
improvement on the forecasts made at the start of the year,
commenting Enel Chairman Chicco Testa.
</P>
<P>
"The Italian economy has definitively joined a virtuous
circle," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
