<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another U.S. Balloon Set to Circle the Globe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- World flight record holder
Dick Rutan and pilot Dave Melton set to launch another balloon
mission to circle the world without stop early Tuesday from New
Mexico after Steve Fossett abandoned his attempt earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rutan and Melton told reporters on Monday that their balloon
will take off at 5 a.m. EST (1000 GMT) near Albuquerque, and
weather forecasters predicted a good weather for their record
attempt.
</P>
<P>
Rutan said their track will favor the more northern latitudes,
reaching Nova Scotia in about two days.
</P>
<P>
Rutan, a 59-year-old Air Force combat pilot, flew his
experimental Voyager plane around the world non-stop without
refueling in December 1986. And Melton, a 39-year-old Albuquerque
balloonist, has the experience of three previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
The 52-meter Global Hilton balloon is expected to rise to a
cruising latitude between 9,750 and 10,970 meters, flying west to
east around the world between the 30th and 50th parallels.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, American adventurer Steve Fossett ended his
around-the-world attempt by landing in southern Russia, after four
and a half days ballooning, covering 11,680 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Another crew, Bertrand Piccard, Wim Verstraeten and Andy Elson,
is set to launch another attempt from Switzerland on Wednesday. on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
