<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene-Based Drug Treatment of Heart Disease on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- A New-York-based hospital is
using a gene-based drug to treat insufficient blood flow to the
heart muscle, believed to be the first case of medical trial in
this area in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The drug, called vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) was
a product of three years of research and experiment on animals,
said Ronald Crystal, M.D., Professor of Medicine at Cornell
University Medical College and Principal Investigator of the
clinical trail.
</P>
<P>
The drug would trigger new blood vessel formation in tissues
deprived of sufficient blood flow due to atherosclerousis or other
conditions.
</P>
<P>
It has been administered to the first patient in a Phase I
clinical trial as an adjunct to traditional coronary bypass
surgeries, he told a press conference at the College here today.
</P>
<P>
The trial started at the New York Hospital-Cornell Medical
Center on December 17 when Dr. Todd K. Rosengart, M.D.,
Co-Principal Investigator of the trial injected the drug to the
oxygen-starved heart muscle of the first patient in the trial.
</P>
<P>
"By inserting this new gene into the heart, we are telling the
heart to detour around the obstructed arteries," Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage, we are testing for safety and establishing an
appropriate dosage level in humans," he added.
</P>
<P>
Crystal said the Phase I would last three to four weeks and it
may take several months for them to watch on how the drug effect
develops. If it works, it will be a milestone in heart disease
treatment, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980106.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Buy 15 Military Helicopters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government announced
today that it will buy 15 new search-and-rescue helicopters for
its military.
</P>
<P>
The Agusta-Westland Cormorant choppers will cost Canada a total
of 790 million dollars (553 million US dollars), Defense Minister
Art Eggleton told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
This includes 593 million dollars for the aircraft and some 200
million dollars to cover project management, training, spare parts
and logistics support.
</P>
<P>
The chopper is a cheaper version of the EH-101, whose contract
was canceled by Jean Chretien's government when it took over just
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Now Canadians will have a helicopter that can do the job at a
price they can afford," Eggleton said.
</P>
<P>
"The competitive process has resulted in a search-and-rescue
helicopter project that is approximately 40 percent less expensive
than the EH-101 order our government terminated in 1993," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
However, today's announcement was criticized by some as
embarrassing turnaround by the Canadian government, which paid the
same consortium 478 million dollars for canceling a deal for 50
EH-101 choppers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
