<HEADLINE> US Dollar Rallies Against Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rallied to a
more than five year high against the Japanese yen today as the
investors still worried about the prospect of the Asian economy.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the U.S. currency was quoted at
133.78 yen, up from 132.55 yen late Friday, its highest point
since reaching 134.45 yen on April 24, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.8263 marks, up from
1.8043 marks Friday, and its highest since settling at 1.8335
marks on September 2.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's rise began in Asian trading after Japan's major
stock index fell by 2 percent on fears of another rocky year for
Japanese business.
</P>
<P>
The dollar extended its gains here after U.S. Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin said that a strong dollar remains in the
interest of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Also boosting the dollar was a rally in U.S. bond prices, which
pushed the long-term interest as low as 5.73 percent, a level
never reached since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The British pound settled at 1.6311 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6440 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
also gained against Swiss francs, French francs, Italian lire and
Canadian dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
