<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Not to Adjust Hardline Policies toward Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States would not
change its hardline policies toward Iraq despite criticism from
other countries for its way handling the Iraqi issues in the U.N.
Security Council, the State department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We're not going to adjust our policies, because we believe
that Iraq poses a grave threat to the region," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said at a regular briefing. "
</P>
<P>
Rubin was answering a question from a reporter who thought the
United States had "lost some momentum, some drive in being able to
maintain sanctions (against Iraq) and to hold the other members of
the Security Council's feet to the fire."
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said that "the perceptions on this issue wax and
wane, and over the years there have been many times when the Unite
States was asked are we going to adjust our policy because the
enthusiasm of some other countries has waxed and waned."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States would stick to its present Iraq
policies as the Iraqis are "determined to thwart the will of the
international community by refusing to own up to what they have
done in the area of weapons of mass destruction, by refusing to
implement U.N. Security Council resolutions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
