<HEADLINE> European Shares Up on Firm Wall Street, Strong Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe all
surged strongly and ended sharply higher today, boosted by a firm
start on Wall Street, a robust dollar and good domestic economic
news.
</P>
<P>
Britain's leading stocks hit a three-month high and closed at
the session's best levels on the first full trading day of the New
Year, with the FTSE 100 index up 69 or 1.33 percent at 5,262.5 as
Wall Street put in a strong performance and international bond
markets remained healthy.
</P>
<P>
UK and US bonds set record highs as fears of near-term interest
rate increases faded. UK financial stocks were key gainers as
banks were squeezed higher.
</P>
<P>
All three major European markets were also underlined by a
strong dollar, which soared to a 5.5-year high against the yen
today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that European market sentiments were further
buoyed by evidence of slower economic growth in both Britain and
Germany, which ruled out near-term interest rate rises in the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended sharply higher on the back of
a strong dollar as the market recovered some of last week's upward
momentum.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index rose by 69.44 points to close at 4,384.81, an
increase of 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris rose by 32.7 points to end at
3,072.84, also supported by a robust dollar, which will boost
exports.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of France decided to leave its key intervention rate
at 3.30 percent as expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
