<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Confident Peace in N.Ireland Still Holding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam said today a shaky truce by Protestant
guerrilla groups was still holding despite a series of violence
last week.
</P>
<P>
"My assessment is that it is fragile but it is holding. I have
had no information to the contrary and on that basis we will move
forward with the ceasefire intact," Mowlam told reporters after a
day of talks with Northern Ireland's multi-party politicians.
</P>
<P>
The emergency meeting was aimed at halting the rot in the
divided province's flagging peace process, undermined by three
guerrilla killings last week.
</P>
<P>
The politicians at the meeting were all determined not to be
deflected from the need to make rapid progress in the search for
peace, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We remain on course for that objective and I want and hope
that all participants will stay with us in getting there," the
secretary added.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Mowlam will meet representatives from IRA political
wing Sinn Fein and the main Protestant Ulster Unionist Party
(UUP), which says Mowlam should resign over the increase in
violence.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Prime Minister Tony Blair held an
hour-long meeting with pro-British UUP leader David Trimble
earlier in the day, which the prime minister's spokesman described
as constructive and positive.
</P>
<P>
"It was a useful opportunity for detailed discussion of the
talks process," he said, describing Blair as still "cautiously
optimistic" despite recent difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
