<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges End to Discrimination Against Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- A UN publication says
that while there has been progress in most countries to end
discrimination against women, there is still no society in the
world where women enjoy full equality with men.
</P>
<P>
To illustrate the discrimination against women, the publication
from the United Nations Division for the Advancement of
Women presents the following fact:
</P>
<P>
-- Two thirds of the world's illiterate adults are women;
</P>
<P>
-- More boys than girls attend school;
</P>
<P>
-- Women do twice the amount of unpaid work than men do;
</P>
<P>
-- Women earn three fourths of what men earn;
</P>
<P>
-- Women's health concerns are often ignored;
</P>
<P>
-- Women are vastly under-represented in positions of power;
</P>
<P>
-- Violence against women is a global epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The publication says that since the beginning, the United
Nations has promoted equality between men and women. Over the
years, it has convened four international conferences to further
women's rights. Today there are five bodies in the United Nation
system devoted to women's issues. There is also an inter-agency
committee that is working to ensure coordination and integration
of a gender perspective into all UN programs and policies.
</P>
<P>
Most important of all, the publication says, the United Nations
has adopted several declarations and conventions which set
international standards for achieving equality between men and
women.
</P>
<P>
Foremost among them is the landmark Convention on the
Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women, the
publication says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
